563
02:17:24,055 --> 02:17:39,641
[SPEAKER_33]: So to sum up the school-based needs, new positions, increased funding for supplies, increased PD, and other school requests, and that total is $987,000.

564
02:17:48,675 --> 02:17:51,618
[SPEAKER_12]: Next up, we're going to go over our facilities and operational needs.

565
02:17:52,259 --> 02:17:55,362
[SPEAKER_15]: Noel, before you continue, can I just ask a general question?

566
02:17:55,442 --> 02:17:58,004
[SPEAKER_15]: What is the percent increase over 2026 budget?

567
02:17:58,125 --> 02:17:59,025
[SPEAKER_15]: It's around 9%.

568
02:18:01,788 --> 02:18:12,279
[SPEAKER_15]: So is this like everybody's wish list, or how are we going to pare this down a bit?

569
02:18:16,618 --> 02:18:31,063
[SPEAKER_33]: They're not wish list, they're identified spending and there's some, we recognize that, you know, we may not be able to get this amount of money.

570
02:18:31,204 --> 02:18:42,407
[SPEAKER_33]: There are some costs identified here that, you know, are not, are kind of bottom line, the collector bargaining for one.

571
02:18:44,622 --> 02:18:48,983
[SPEAKER_33]: real some of the IEP spending.

572
02:18:52,225 --> 02:18:57,826
[SPEAKER_33]: There might be a little bit of wiggle room to defer some of the spending into 28.

573
02:18:59,407 --> 02:19:08,770
[SPEAKER_33]: We've pretty much screened out the spending that we thought were a little more wish list than actual need.

574
02:19:11,114 --> 02:19:23,044
[SPEAKER_33]: You know, for facilities, you know, we'll, as always, deferred maintenance is kind of a tried and true method when you don't have sufficient funds.

575
02:19:25,286 --> 02:19:31,972
[SPEAKER_33]: But we could rely, for instance, for special ed transportation, we could rely

576
02:19:32,963 --> 02:19:35,044
[SPEAKER_33]: more heavily on circuit breaker funds.

577
02:19:35,104 --> 02:19:46,309
[SPEAKER_33]: So we're trying, we're trying to strike a balance as how much circuit breaker we need, we use in one fiscal year and how much we want to save following fiscal year.

578
02:19:47,469 --> 02:19:58,895
[SPEAKER_33]: Um, there's money in, uh, uh, the homeless transportation reimbursement account that we could tap, uh, to try to reduce the budget.

579
02:19:59,015 --> 02:19:59,635
[SPEAKER_33]: But, um,

580
02:20:01,307 --> 02:20:04,108
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah, I mean, we can only tax at 2.5%, so.

581
02:20:04,928 --> 02:20:05,088
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah.

582
02:20:06,689 --> 02:20:08,189
[SPEAKER_15]: And we got health insurance that went up 10%.

583
02:20:08,229 --> 02:20:14,712
[SPEAKER_15]: We have the debt we have to repay, starting to repay for the McGlynn and the Andrews HVAC work.

584
02:20:15,692 --> 02:20:17,472
[SPEAKER_15]: So the money's just not there.

585
02:20:17,913 --> 02:20:18,093
[SPEAKER_33]: Yeah.

586
02:20:20,013 --> 02:20:24,535
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, this is a starting point, and then we will.

587
02:20:25,795 --> 02:20:31,759
[SPEAKER_33]: We will absolutely present, you know, in the final budget.

588
02:20:31,979 --> 02:20:36,361
[SPEAKER_33]: So, you know, in our budget development policy, this is a preliminary budget.

589
02:20:37,102 --> 02:20:41,564
[SPEAKER_33]: It will be eventually a final budget and that budget will be balanced.

590
02:20:43,846 --> 02:20:44,726
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you, Mr. McHugh.

591
02:20:44,746 --> 02:20:53,651
[SPEAKER_13]: That was the only thing I was just going to clarify which is why I wanted to frame at the beginning that this is preliminary as part of the school committee policy and just

592
02:20:55,029 --> 02:20:57,531
[SPEAKER_13]: wanted to be very transparent about what the asks were.

593
02:20:58,412 --> 02:21:09,740
[SPEAKER_13]: What is presented here tonight does align to our instructional vision, our strategic initiatives and our core values.

594
02:21:09,940 --> 02:21:17,285
[SPEAKER_13]: But we know, as I said, it's very iterative and still there's refining to do.

595
02:21:19,165 --> 02:21:20,586
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah, yeah, this is $5 million off.

596
02:21:20,646 --> 02:21:23,869
[SPEAKER_15]: I mean, I have to wipe out half the city departments to pay for this.

597
02:21:23,889 --> 02:21:25,551
[SPEAKER_15]: I don't know which one you want me to get rid of.

598
02:21:26,272 --> 02:21:35,920
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah.

599
02:21:35,961 --> 02:21:38,623
[SPEAKER_12]: Next up, we're going to go over facilities and operational needs.

600
02:21:43,991 --> 02:21:56,076
[SPEAKER_12]: After some extensive talk with myself, superintendent, and our new COO, Ken Lord, we reviewed a few areas and facilities that we really want to address and work hard on.

601
02:21:57,556 --> 02:22:02,618
[SPEAKER_12]: First step here is we were at a fourth carpenter slash maintenance worker.

602
02:22:03,678 --> 02:22:11,001
[SPEAKER_12]: Based on the amount of work in the schools and the amount of overtime we're paying to the maintenance workers, we believe that we can get a lot accomplished with adding an extra employee

603
02:22:11,924 --> 02:22:14,245
[SPEAKER_12]: who can really bang out a lot of things.

604
02:22:14,325 --> 02:22:22,847
[SPEAKER_12]: As you know, we currently have three maintenance workers who oversee all the school departments, which is just, can backlog a lot of areas.

605
02:22:26,468 --> 02:22:35,810
[SPEAKER_12]: Based off of our fiscal year 25 invoice analysis and our fiscal year 26 projections, we're looking to increase the contract and maintenance lines by $359,000.

606
02:22:42,101 --> 02:23:03,043
[SPEAKER_12]: We have from the Habeeb and Associates assessment project, hoping to increase the extraordinary maintenance line by $70,000 to replace the water heater tank, number two at the Roberts Elementary School, and $7,000 in increase for equipment repair line items.

607
02:23:08,682 --> 02:23:13,324
[SPEAKER_12]: Over in our technology department, we're hoping to add a little bit more technology infrastructure.

608
02:23:14,324 --> 02:23:19,006
[SPEAKER_12]: We're currently with a cybersecurity package that includes other software increases at $52,000.

609
02:23:19,406 --> 02:23:31,870
[SPEAKER_12]: So in total, based on our facility needs and technology needs, we believe $554,255 would be the increase.

610
02:23:39,000 --> 02:23:55,454
[SPEAKER_12]: On the next slide here, you have just an idea of some of the maintenance services that the Metropublic Schools uses throughout the year, from pest management to concrete repairs, heating, HVAC, fire extinguisher inspections.

611
02:23:56,114 --> 02:24:02,660
[SPEAKER_12]: Those numbers can get up there pretty quickly, but we just wanted to give an idea of exactly everything Ken Lord does for us in overseas.

612
02:24:06,597 --> 02:24:08,599
[SPEAKER_12]: Next up we have some identified savings.

613
02:24:14,523 --> 02:24:22,409
[SPEAKER_12]: So with the enrollment of the special needs programs at the Brooks Elementary School, we would go from five classrooms to four classrooms.

614
02:24:22,529 --> 02:24:26,252
[SPEAKER_12]: We would have two learning groups and two language based groups.

615
02:24:28,273 --> 02:24:34,578
[SPEAKER_12]: There would be no FTE losses as we have a teacher who's retiring and that position would not be filled.

616
02:24:35,608 --> 02:24:40,369
[SPEAKER_12]: And then the parent in their classroom would be absorbed into a vacant position at the end of the fiscal year.

617
02:24:42,449 --> 02:24:46,470
[SPEAKER_12]: We have our ELA curriculum payment for Houghton Mifflin.

618
02:24:46,510 --> 02:24:51,211
[SPEAKER_12]: We just finished paying off our third payment this fiscal year, so that is completely done.

619
02:24:53,172 --> 02:24:59,593
[SPEAKER_12]: Our new contracts for telephone and copier lease save us approximately $95,000 to $62,000.

620
02:25:01,053 --> 02:25:04,554
[SPEAKER_12]: We have our NEASC accreditation expenses, which we completed this year.

621
02:25:05,769 --> 02:25:09,371
[SPEAKER_12]: So that's another $30,000 from last year's budget that we would take off.

622
02:25:10,472 --> 02:25:21,758
[SPEAKER_12]: And then just miscellaneous line items are whether it's little things that we purchased this year or just balancing from positives in one area and negatives in one area, we came up with a $14,000 savings.

623
02:25:21,798 --> 02:25:24,060
[SPEAKER_12]: Total identified savings of $490,991.

624
02:25:24,100 --> 02:25:25,340
[SPEAKER_12]: And we have here a few no-cost proposals.

625
02:25:37,947 --> 02:25:41,150
[SPEAKER_12]: We'd like to add two AM, PM, meet classrooms at the Brooks.

626
02:25:43,592 --> 02:25:44,333
[SPEAKER_12]: Convert to full day.

627
02:25:44,353 --> 02:25:45,133
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes, I'm sorry about that.

628
02:25:45,153 --> 02:25:45,313
[SPEAKER_12]: Yep.

629
02:25:45,714 --> 02:25:46,614
[SPEAKER_12]: Convert to full day.

630
02:25:48,476 --> 02:25:52,019
[SPEAKER_12]: We currently have a vacancy for a literacy coach.

631
02:25:52,199 --> 02:25:54,861
[SPEAKER_12]: We'd like to convert that position to a math coach for fiscal year 27.

632
02:25:57,128 --> 02:26:04,690
[SPEAKER_12]: And then we will be piloting a composting program at the high school in the Mississippi, but only the back end of the kitchen.

633
02:26:04,750 --> 02:26:06,951
[SPEAKER_12]: So that's where all the cooking is done.

634
02:26:07,211 --> 02:26:10,492
[SPEAKER_12]: And that would be covered on the food service department budget.

635
02:26:14,853 --> 02:26:18,494
[SPEAKER_12]: And then we have here is just our summary based on our first slide.

636
02:26:23,325 --> 02:26:42,558
[SPEAKER_12]: As we spoke about earlier, our general fund and stabilization fund, which total $86 million, and then our estimated salary step increases, our unavoidable cost increases, the request from principals and directors, the request from our facilities and our identified savings comes in at $94,032,696.

637
02:26:49,020 --> 02:26:55,865
[SPEAKER_12]: And on the next slide, you'll just get an idea of what the increases and decreases would look like based on actual numbers.

638
02:26:56,565 --> 02:27:03,410
[SPEAKER_12]: From our appropriation general fund, our stabilization fund that we would add next year, that's 750,000, which gets us to our total number, $94,032,696.

639
02:27:03,910 --> 02:27:05,011
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you all for your time.

640
02:27:05,111 --> 02:27:06,912
[SPEAKER_12]: That is our presentation.

641
02:27:06,952 --> 02:27:09,174
[SPEAKER_12]: Of course, we're here to answer any and all questions you have.

