02:27:47,035 --> 02:27:48,296
[SPEAKER_30]: It's just a standard line item.

652
02:27:48,516 --> 02:27:48,796
[SPEAKER_30]: Thank you.

653
02:27:48,816 --> 02:27:54,637
[SPEAKER_33]: So these are what was the increases to base budget.

654
02:27:54,717 --> 02:27:56,317
[SPEAKER_33]: So that's in our base budget.

655
02:28:08,724 --> 02:28:10,545
[SPEAKER_15]: Member Graham, then Member Mastropone.

656
02:28:12,386 --> 02:28:12,826
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

657
02:28:14,667 --> 02:28:26,814
[SPEAKER_07]: I know that the state budget is still making its way through the process, but we are once again a minimum aid city and the governor's budget proposed minimum aid at $75 a student.

658
02:28:26,894 --> 02:28:28,095
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that correct?

659
02:28:34,391 --> 02:28:35,432
[SPEAKER_07]: Was it 75 or 70?

660
02:28:37,494 --> 02:28:35,432
70.

661
02:28:38,975 --> 02:28:43,399
[SPEAKER_07]: Has the House or the Senate budget been released yet?

662
02:28:44,099 --> 02:28:47,943
[SPEAKER_07]: I know that they always tend to move that number a little bit.

663
02:28:47,963 --> 02:28:48,883
[SPEAKER_33]: Not since yesterday.

664
02:28:48,903 --> 02:28:48,943
[SPEAKER_33]: OK.

665
02:28:49,064 --> 02:28:53,187
[SPEAKER_33]: And last year the minimum was $150 per student.

666
02:28:53,427 --> 02:28:53,627
[SPEAKER_07]: Right.

667
02:28:54,148 --> 02:29:00,033
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think they're grappling with some of the same challenges all around.

668
02:29:01,415 --> 02:29:03,076
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think that's something to look for.

669
02:29:03,116 --> 02:29:05,877
[SPEAKER_07]: So this is like year seven of the Student Opportunity Act.

670
02:29:06,737 --> 02:29:10,278
[SPEAKER_07]: There was only one year where we received more than minimum aid.

671
02:29:12,019 --> 02:29:14,260
[SPEAKER_07]: And this is another minimum aid year.

672
02:29:14,340 --> 02:29:23,503
[SPEAKER_07]: So presuming that the you know any change to minimum aid would be a boost to our you know to our numbers.

673
02:29:25,568 --> 02:29:30,671
[SPEAKER_07]: I assume that some so I just think from a grounding perspective.

674
02:29:31,932 --> 02:29:42,477
[SPEAKER_07]: This is a picture of like the starting point of a budget request that says for us to meet the objectives of the district and to do to meet our obligations contractually.

675
02:29:42,798 --> 02:29:47,020
[SPEAKER_07]: This is what the numbers look like and we'll approve.

676
02:29:47,537 --> 02:29:56,401
[SPEAKER_07]: some version of this at our next meeting coming up, and then that will go to the mayor and the council as a request.

677
02:29:57,281 --> 02:30:10,707
[SPEAKER_07]: And then once the council and the mayor determine what those numbers actually are, to your point, Jerry, before we end the fiscal year, hopefully, there would be another conversation to say like,

678
02:30:11,057 --> 02:30:15,120
[SPEAKER_07]: is if there is a gap, how do we close that gap and potentially like another public hearing?

679
02:30:15,720 --> 02:30:30,451
[SPEAKER_07]: So between now and then, I assume there will be lots of things going on from a funding perspective, like from a like analysis of funding options that might be outside of just a direct ask from the city, is that true?

680
02:30:31,472 --> 02:30:31,692
[SPEAKER_33]: Yes.

681
02:30:33,653 --> 02:30:39,658
[SPEAKER_33]: We do have an obligation to schedule a public hearing before the vote on the budget.

682
02:30:40,295 --> 02:30:45,451
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes and then I think the other question I had which was on page.

683
02:30:48,541 --> 02:30:51,263
[SPEAKER_07]: 18 for facilities and operations.

684
02:30:52,403 --> 02:30:58,748
[SPEAKER_07]: One of the things that this outlines is an increase in our contracted maintenance line items.

685
02:30:59,068 --> 02:31:07,294
[SPEAKER_07]: Can you is that because we will save money by contracting folks in these spaces?

686
02:31:07,754 --> 02:31:11,397
[SPEAKER_07]: Are we already spending this money or has like had the cost just like

687
02:31:13,187 --> 02:31:36,467
[SPEAKER_07]: risen dramatically like if we if we don't do this what happens I think is part of my question but I mean three people for a district of this size is like super anemic and it's not shocking that we have the maintenance issues that we have because we've been staffed this way forever and I know that one of the things that we've been talking about as we continue to negotiate with our bargaining partners is how do we you know how do we set up

688
02:31:37,009 --> 02:31:39,131
[SPEAKER_07]: that unit in a productive way.

689
02:31:39,972 --> 02:31:48,642
[SPEAKER_07]: But I'm just curious, like, what the balance of internal staff to contracted services really should be for a district of our size?

690
02:31:48,742 --> 02:31:52,446
[SPEAKER_07]: And, like, how does this proposal fit into, like, moving towards something that is more ideal?

691
02:31:53,184 --> 02:32:04,948
[SPEAKER_33]: I'm gonna turn it over to Ken Lord in a second, but if you remember last year, I think just for starters, our maintenance budget was woefully underfunded.

692
02:32:05,868 --> 02:32:15,872
[SPEAKER_33]: We proposed a more realistic budget last year, and in the final negotiations of the budget,

693
02:32:16,900 --> 02:32:24,065
[SPEAKER_33]: We were given some stabilization fund money for specific projects, which we're grateful for.

694
02:32:24,925 --> 02:32:25,786
[SPEAKER_33]: That helped a lot.

695
02:32:26,486 --> 02:32:32,930
[SPEAKER_33]: But we had to reduce our maintenance ask by an equivalent amount.

696
02:32:32,990 --> 02:32:36,752
[SPEAKER_33]: So that's kind of how we negotiated the gap last year.

697
02:32:39,273 --> 02:32:49,958
[SPEAKER_33]: while we were able to get some money for projects, we didn't really move the maintenance budgets forward, which we will ask for now.

698
02:32:50,378 --> 02:33:06,925
[SPEAKER_33]: And basically, the mix of in-house versus private, you know, varies from district to district and based on your capacity, your in-house capacity.

699
02:33:07,545 --> 02:33:09,006
[SPEAKER_33]: the type of systems you have.

700
02:33:10,688 --> 02:33:14,631
[SPEAKER_33]: But I'll let Ken expand on this.

701
02:33:15,792 --> 02:33:17,674
[SPEAKER_38]: Yes, exactly what Jerry was just saying.

702
02:33:17,954 --> 02:33:25,440
[SPEAKER_38]: We use our in-house staff to do all the tasks that we feel we are qualified and capable of doing up to the limit of the staff time that we have.

703
02:33:25,900 --> 02:33:34,247
[SPEAKER_38]: So we do farm out work that we could potentially do in-house if we had more staff in-house, and we could do it more economically

704
02:33:34,988 --> 02:33:38,792
[SPEAKER_38]: with in-house staff because you always pay more for bringing in somebody from the outside.

705
02:33:39,252 --> 02:33:45,979
[SPEAKER_38]: There are quite a few tasks that we just don't have the skill nor should we to do in-house, you know, some real heavy repairs.

706
02:33:46,359 --> 02:33:48,741
[SPEAKER_38]: We don't have licensed electricians on staff.

707
02:33:49,182 --> 02:33:56,349
[SPEAKER_38]: We need certain kind of, you know, people to do different kinds of work that will kind of always farm out inspections, elevator, you know, those kinds of things.

708
02:33:57,850 --> 02:34:03,351
[SPEAKER_38]: We're really struggling to keep up with the load of things that we can do in-house with the staff that we have.

709
02:34:03,792 --> 02:34:04,912
[SPEAKER_38]: They work incredibly hard.

710
02:34:04,932 --> 02:34:05,912
[SPEAKER_38]: They're incredibly skilled.

711
02:34:05,932 --> 02:34:06,852
[SPEAKER_38]: There's just not enough of them.

712
02:34:08,233 --> 02:34:19,095
[SPEAKER_38]: And what I did to build the amount of contract services in the request this year is I looked at all the expenses from last year, told them up in different categories, and then we broke it up in each sum.

713
02:34:19,575 --> 02:34:21,416
[SPEAKER_38]: We did it a little differently in the budget, so we really

714
02:34:22,256 --> 02:34:32,683
[SPEAKER_38]: identified which type of contract we would have, and that's going to enable me to go out to bid for contractors, whereas now we really rely on the state tradesmen contracts to do it piecemeal.

715
02:34:32,703 --> 02:34:34,564
[SPEAKER_38]: I hope that answers all your questions.

716
02:34:34,644 --> 02:34:34,905
[SPEAKER_07]: It does.

717
02:34:34,945 --> 02:34:38,747
[SPEAKER_38]: Thank you.

718
02:34:39,828 --> 02:34:40,728
[SPEAKER_14]: Member Mastroboni?

719
02:34:44,411 --> 02:34:44,591
[SPEAKER_31]: Yes.

720
02:34:47,352 --> 02:34:47,972
[SPEAKER_31]: Oh, member Rousseau.

721
02:34:48,192 --> 02:34:48,492
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you.

722
02:34:48,692 --> 02:34:52,553
[SPEAKER_31]: And I think you said this last year, but I've already forgotten.

723
02:34:52,613 --> 02:34:52,893
[SPEAKER_31]: Sorry.

724
02:34:53,674 --> 02:34:58,035
[SPEAKER_31]: What is a typical number of maintenance workers with this many buildings in a district?

725
02:34:58,535 --> 02:34:59,595
[SPEAKER_38]: It really varies.

726
02:35:00,335 --> 02:35:04,156
[SPEAKER_38]: I tried to do some study around some surrounding cities and towns.

727
02:35:04,736 --> 02:35:07,657
[SPEAKER_38]: They really vary wildly just based upon what they farm out.

728
02:35:08,937 --> 02:35:14,339
[SPEAKER_38]: And it's really kind of a function of what you can afford to do internally in the age of some of your buildings.

729
02:35:14,999 --> 02:35:22,981
[SPEAKER_38]: You know, the older buildings take a lot more maintenance, a lot more upkeep, but they are often more easily done in-house because their older systems are not as complex.

730
02:35:24,081 --> 02:35:28,422
[SPEAKER_38]: So, for instance, the newer HVAC systems that we're installing really need to be farmed out stuff.

731
02:35:29,322 --> 02:35:35,063
[SPEAKER_38]: You know, we really need to be able to, you know, have people that are expert in those systems that we're installing now maintain them.

732
02:35:35,123 --> 02:35:41,725
[SPEAKER_38]: So, you're going to see things that our crews can handle internally need to be done externally moving forward.

733
02:35:41,905 --> 02:35:42,245
[SPEAKER_31]: So, it's.

734
02:35:45,513 --> 02:35:52,538
[SPEAKER_31]: really outside, you know, if you had one of those bell curves, is it like one of those little tiny numbers way at the end, and you're like, hey, we can't find us there.

735
02:35:52,979 --> 02:36:00,325
[SPEAKER_38]: Yeah, my initial reaction, and the one, this is my seventh month in, is confirmed after being seven months, is we are woefully understaffed.

736
02:36:01,125 --> 02:36:02,967
[SPEAKER_38]: I can't keep up with basic stuff that we can do.

737
02:36:03,627 --> 02:36:08,751
[SPEAKER_38]: And, you know, just to bring in an outside contractor, it costs you a thousand dollars just to have them walk in the door, you know, so.

738
02:36:09,151 --> 02:36:09,792
[SPEAKER_38]: Okay, thanks.

739
02:36:12,747 --> 02:36:14,028
[SPEAKER_15]: We're in the same boat on the city side.

740
02:36:15,308 --> 02:36:16,108
[SPEAKER_15]: Member Mastroboni.

741
02:36:18,289 --> 02:36:19,010
[SPEAKER_35]: Excuse me.

742
02:36:19,050 --> 02:36:19,370
[SPEAKER_35]: Thank you.

743
02:36:20,170 --> 02:36:27,213
[SPEAKER_35]: So I think the phrase unavoidable cost is bugging me a little bit.

744
02:36:27,233 --> 02:36:29,694
[SPEAKER_35]: I think there's a combination of a lot of things in there.

745
02:36:29,714 --> 02:36:33,456
[SPEAKER_15]: Reinfeld, if you could shut yours off.

746
02:36:33,516 --> 02:36:35,157
[SPEAKER_15]: Everybody shut it off.

747
02:36:35,177 --> 02:36:35,457
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

748
02:36:35,577 --> 02:36:36,678
[SPEAKER_15]: Member Mastroboni, you have the floor.

749
02:36:37,318 --> 02:36:37,638
[SPEAKER_35]: Thanks, Ken.

750
02:36:38,486 --> 02:36:45,154
[SPEAKER_35]: I mean, I think it varies, right, from things that would look like compliance, right, special ed resources.

751
02:36:45,174 --> 02:36:47,697
[SPEAKER_35]: There's a lot of budget right sizing, which I think is great.

752
02:36:47,737 --> 02:36:50,841
[SPEAKER_35]: That's, you know, shows that you all are looking backwards to move forwards.

753
02:36:51,462 --> 02:36:53,044
[SPEAKER_35]: I also think there's some choices in there.

754
02:36:53,064 --> 02:36:54,926
[SPEAKER_35]: You know, I think I wholeheartedly support.

755
02:36:55,407 --> 02:37:01,235
[SPEAKER_35]: moving paras off revolving funds, right, in concept, but that feels like a choice at this time.

756
02:37:03,017 --> 02:37:05,661
[SPEAKER_35]: So, you know, this is a great list of needs.

757
02:37:05,681 --> 02:37:06,662
[SPEAKER_35]: It's not surprising.

758
02:37:07,443 --> 02:37:10,087
[SPEAKER_35]: There's a lot going on and there's a lot of work to do and a lot of improvements to make.

759
02:37:12,028 --> 02:37:14,289
[SPEAKER_35]: Mayor Lincoln Kern also talked about a $5 million gap.

760
02:37:15,290 --> 02:37:36,399
[SPEAKER_35]: So I'm wondering what the process is behind the scenes that you all and with the superintendent are undertaking over the course of the next month to identify what's highest priority of these marginal changes, what's highest priority of our existing expenditures to understand, to identify the least painful reductions here.

761
02:37:38,220 --> 02:37:39,021
[SPEAKER_35]: These are a lot of great ideas.

762
02:37:39,041 --> 02:37:41,582
[SPEAKER_35]: Where do we go from here, I think is my question.

763
02:37:44,192 --> 02:37:44,412
[SPEAKER_35]: pair.

764
02:37:46,536 --> 02:37:53,106
[SPEAKER_15]: And just to piggyback on that, to put something before us that's $5 million, it just makes

765
02:37:53,696 --> 02:38:04,782
[SPEAKER_15]: the community, whoever's watching, it makes it seem like we're as bad off as other local cities and towns that have just lost a big override, two of whom touch us.

766
02:38:06,003 --> 02:38:21,532
[SPEAKER_15]: So it just makes us look bad, and we'll talk Wednesday about, you know, the deficit that I'll handle on the city side, but cutting city budgets to give a little more to the schools, like I always do it, and I'll do it again, but when you bring something that's five million over, it just seems like,

767
02:38:22,916 --> 02:38:25,237
[SPEAKER_15]: some of that job could have been done before tonight.

768
02:38:27,078 --> 02:38:27,618
[SPEAKER_15]: Member Russo.

769
02:38:28,139 --> 02:38:28,519
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you.

770
02:38:29,819 --> 02:38:42,205
[SPEAKER_31]: In June of 2024, we approved our budget preparation schedule and very much the point of that was to have this exact conversation.

771
02:38:42,566 --> 02:38:47,368
[SPEAKER_31]: If the answer was it was another $40 million to accomplish the goals of the district, then that's the answer.

772
02:38:48,829 --> 02:38:50,649
[SPEAKER_31]: The time to talk about what we have to cut is

773
02:38:52,923 --> 02:38:55,024
[SPEAKER_31]: is in the schedule and we have to do it.

774
02:38:55,344 --> 02:38:58,286
[SPEAKER_31]: And there's no, nobody imagines we're gonna find all this money.

775
02:38:59,647 --> 02:39:06,911
[SPEAKER_31]: But to not tell the public and just treat them like adults, that hey, to operate the district at, well, this is minimum.

776
02:39:07,111 --> 02:39:11,493
[SPEAKER_31]: If you looked at the total new ads, it was like 500,000 here and 400,000 like.

777
02:39:11,934 --> 02:39:16,256
[SPEAKER_31]: Those are not numbers that make you think we're dramatically improving the district at all.

778
02:39:16,856 --> 02:39:17,317
[SPEAKER_31]: They are not.

779
02:39:17,897 --> 02:39:18,037
[SPEAKER_31]: So

780
02:39:18,547 --> 02:39:23,011
[SPEAKER_31]: This, this budget does not, in my mind, move the district particularly forward.

781
02:39:23,651 --> 02:39:25,232
[SPEAKER_31]: This keeps the district afloat.

782
02:39:26,934 --> 02:39:30,236
[SPEAKER_31]: This, this budget request, this isn't the budget, this is the budget request.

783
02:39:30,297 --> 02:39:37,422
[SPEAKER_31]: And I think we have to tell the public what it actually costs to do the job they think we're doing or want us to be doing.

784
02:39:38,763 --> 02:39:43,247
[SPEAKER_31]: And then we can have the, the other adult conversation when we have to figure out, okay, we have to cut.

785
02:39:43,715 --> 02:39:48,619
[SPEAKER_31]: Whether it's 5 million or 4 million or 3 million, there's no cutting that kind of money without laying people off.

786
02:39:48,739 --> 02:39:50,260
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm gonna be the first to say it.

787
02:39:50,380 --> 02:39:51,601
[SPEAKER_31]: Like, I looked at those numbers.

788
02:39:51,701 --> 02:39:53,482
[SPEAKER_31]: We're gonna not, not pay electricity.

789
02:39:54,103 --> 02:39:59,447
[SPEAKER_31]: We're not gonna not pay for, you know, all the other things that aren't people.

790
02:39:59,467 --> 02:40:02,289
[SPEAKER_31]: 85% or something of our budget is people.

791
02:40:02,830 --> 02:40:09,895
[SPEAKER_31]: So, when we go from what we believe we need to what we actually have, we're,

792
02:40:10,350 --> 02:40:13,431
[SPEAKER_31]: There's no scenario where that does not include layoffs.

793
02:40:13,971 --> 02:40:19,032
[SPEAKER_31]: So I mean, unless I'm really bad at math, which is possible.

794
02:40:19,972 --> 02:40:37,276
[SPEAKER_31]: But this process we, we vetted and approved in 2024 specifically so the public would know what we as a body believe it would cost to perform the duty that we're elected to perform and that the professionals are hired to

795
02:40:39,192 --> 02:41:01,341
[SPEAKER_31]: to execute on, so I think that's, I agree it's incredibly awkward to be saying this, like, that's a lot more money than we're gonna have, and we're gonna have some ugly conversations, and I hope the school committee's involved in those, not just the administration, we like magically come back with here's the new number, but we have to tell the public the truth.

796
02:41:02,222 --> 02:41:07,164
[SPEAKER_31]: This is our needs assessment to do, frankly, no more in Medford Public Schools than we did this year.

797
02:41:09,952 --> 02:41:10,813
[SPEAKER_14]: Member Master Boney.

798
02:41:12,333 --> 02:41:14,715
[SPEAKER_35]: Briefly, members, I totally agree 100 percent.

799
02:41:14,735 --> 02:41:15,916
[SPEAKER_35]: I'm not asking for cuts.

800
02:41:15,956 --> 02:41:29,484
[SPEAKER_35]: I'm asking to understand the process by which you all decide what's level service, what's service expansion in this big list, what's mostly tied to our district goals, right, so that we can make sure to explain those to residents.

801
02:41:31,105 --> 02:41:36,887
[SPEAKER_35]: And that, so that I can understand the work that you all are doing to identify the risks and trade-offs of different choices that we're gonna make.

802
02:41:37,427 --> 02:41:41,109
[SPEAKER_35]: So, you know, when I see a big list, my eyes kinda glaze over, right?

803
02:41:41,149 --> 02:41:53,913
[SPEAKER_35]: I wanna understand, again, like, you know, where, summarizing where we're investing, what's compliance, what's level service, what's expansion, what's catching back up from something that we learned throughout the course of the year, again, sort of in a summary, this list.

804
02:41:54,273 --> 02:41:58,755
[SPEAKER_35]: It's tough to digest it, even in the couple times I've looked at it since we got it.

805
02:41:59,616 --> 02:42:01,259
[SPEAKER_35]: So, that's the kind of information I'm looking at.

806
02:42:01,279 --> 02:42:04,626
[SPEAKER_35]: And again, not to cut, but to understand where we're at in terms of priorities.

807
02:42:04,646 --> 02:42:08,273
[SPEAKER_33]: Do you want to?

808
02:42:09,134 --> 02:42:10,076
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, we, I think.

809
02:42:13,048 --> 02:42:20,111
[SPEAKER_33]: That will, when we come back to the committee, we will show you how we reduce the budget.

810
02:42:22,052 --> 02:42:30,575
[SPEAKER_33]: One thing that is ongoing, the superintendent did say that we continue to polish these numbers.

811
02:42:32,736 --> 02:42:44,063
[SPEAKER_33]: We've identified pockets of very low class size in some schools, so we're going to be talking to principals about that.

812
02:42:45,443 --> 02:42:46,904
[SPEAKER_33]: That could provide some savings.

813
02:42:51,764 --> 02:43:01,391
[SPEAKER_33]: And then we'll let the high school finish their scheduling to see how that shakes out.

814
02:43:01,932 --> 02:43:18,644
[SPEAKER_33]: So this budget, you know, we tried to, with the exception of that one special needs classroom at the Brooks, which was very clear, we didn't want to talk about personnel right now.

815
02:43:20,145 --> 02:43:25,768
[SPEAKER_33]: But certainly, we have to look at that, you know, to get down to this number.

816
02:43:26,308 --> 02:43:37,412
[SPEAKER_33]: I will say that, you know, the supplies and materials requests are based on the assistant superintendent's initiative to make our

817
02:43:40,183 --> 02:43:43,005
[SPEAKER_33]: instructional offerings more robust, more rigorous.

818
02:43:44,927 --> 02:43:51,292
[SPEAKER_33]: And so we have to buy, you know, better quality materials to make that happen.

819
02:43:53,694 --> 02:44:03,703
[SPEAKER_33]: But I hear what you're saying, so we'll try to address that when we come back for at least a public hearing or maybe before then.

820
02:44:07,672 --> 02:44:08,172
[SPEAKER_13]: If I may.

821
02:44:08,913 --> 02:44:09,453
[SPEAKER_13]: Dr. Lucey.

822
02:44:10,614 --> 02:44:11,815
[SPEAKER_13]: I do want to just comment.

823
02:44:11,975 --> 02:44:18,518
[SPEAKER_13]: So the ongoing conversations that we're having as central leadership with school leaders with the department leaders.

824
02:44:20,240 --> 02:44:36,089
[SPEAKER_13]: As I said we're having conversations about what the priorities are and where are those places that we can reduce and where are those places that we want to be able to kind of hold firm in order to meet our instructional vision.

825
02:44:36,829 --> 02:44:42,051
[SPEAKER_13]: It's never, I think that's why I started this evening with a little bit of framing.

826
02:44:42,611 --> 02:44:50,793
[SPEAKER_13]: It's never, ever my intention to come to a school committee meeting and present something that I feel is going to divide a community.

827
02:44:51,413 --> 02:44:57,295
[SPEAKER_13]: Rather, there's been lots of messaging around transparency and what are those costs.

828
02:44:57,455 --> 02:44:59,616
[SPEAKER_13]: And so, I just wanted to make sure.

829
02:45:00,416 --> 02:45:03,217
[SPEAKER_13]: in this process that we provided that level of transparency.

830
02:45:03,858 --> 02:45:18,164
[SPEAKER_13]: As mentioned by some school committee members as well as Jerry and Noel, there are pieces on there that maybe we're trying to move, let's, when we're talking about the revolving, revolving accounts.

831
02:45:19,204 --> 02:45:24,526
[SPEAKER_13]: Things around materials to enhance curriculum.

832
02:45:25,807 --> 02:45:36,896
[SPEAKER_13]: There's also pieces around some of our entitlement grants that Dr. Talbot and I have been having conversations around, making sure that we're maybe being a little bit more strategic about leveraging that.

833
02:45:37,416 --> 02:45:39,538
[SPEAKER_13]: We also are in talks.

834
02:45:40,819 --> 02:45:41,079
[SPEAKER_13]: We have

835
02:45:42,273 --> 02:45:50,419
[SPEAKER_13]: applied, I'm not quite sure yet of the award, but we have applied for our second round of bar grant funding.

836
02:45:51,020 --> 02:46:00,867
[SPEAKER_13]: That also will drastically inform this budget in terms of what we can put on that bar foundation grant and what we cannot.

837
02:46:02,188 --> 02:46:10,294
[SPEAKER_13]: So between grant funding and our revolving accounts and just making some of those choices that member Masturbone is talking about.

838
02:46:12,079 --> 02:46:28,949
[SPEAKER_13]: This tonight is just to show you what it would take to operationalize completely and fully without having to rely on any sort of grant funding or entitlements.

839
02:46:29,449 --> 02:46:31,671
[SPEAKER_13]: It's certainly not at all to

840
02:46:33,173 --> 02:46:36,155
[SPEAKER_13]: cause any sort of turmoil or stress or division.

841
02:46:36,175 --> 02:46:41,239
[SPEAKER_13]: I apologize if, if that impact hit for people in the community.

842
02:46:41,699 --> 02:46:44,862
[SPEAKER_13]: But this is just, as I said, this is a new team.

843
02:46:45,542 --> 02:46:55,570
[SPEAKER_13]: And so sometimes pushing through to, to make some change and add some structures where there haven't been any, or places where there have been some underfunding.

844
02:46:56,250 --> 02:46:59,633
[SPEAKER_13]: Right now you are seeing some pieces in, that are needed for

845
02:47:01,162 --> 02:47:03,566
[SPEAKER_13]: operationally as well as educationally.

846
02:47:03,606 --> 02:47:05,288
[SPEAKER_13]: But this is not the end.

847
02:47:05,749 --> 02:47:10,635
[SPEAKER_13]: And we will be settling in the uncomfortable work.

848
02:47:11,316 --> 02:47:13,399
[SPEAKER_13]: But I just wanted to make that known.

849
02:47:18,125 --> 02:47:18,626
[SPEAKER_14]: Member Reinfeld?

850
02:47:19,863 --> 02:47:20,383
[SPEAKER_28]: Thank you.

851
02:47:21,424 --> 02:47:29,490
[SPEAKER_28]: So I have all kinds of nitpicky questions, things like, is that the theater teacher we've been talking about for the last two years?

852
02:47:29,910 --> 02:47:41,718
[SPEAKER_28]: But what I really want to ask you about here in this, what is essentially our budget committee of the whole, just as much as it is a regular meeting, some of these

853
02:47:43,838 --> 02:47:50,101
[SPEAKER_28]: Costs for software, instructional materials, curricula, all of those.

854
02:47:50,919 --> 02:48:08,810
[SPEAKER_28]: What I'm not seeing in this summary is, are those expected to be the same costs year upon year, or is this, or are these one-time costs that we won't have to, is it investing in buying the software, or is it a subscription that we're gonna be paying year after year?

855
02:48:08,870 --> 02:48:17,915
[SPEAKER_28]: So there are, I think, one, two, three, four, five, six things that I flagged as wondering whether those are year upon year.

856
02:48:19,123 --> 02:48:24,068
[SPEAKER_28]: And things like the 360 boards, right?

857
02:48:24,088 --> 02:48:25,689
[SPEAKER_28]: You said this is a five year process.

858
02:48:26,049 --> 02:48:27,090
[SPEAKER_28]: Are we front loading it?

859
02:48:27,250 --> 02:48:28,912
[SPEAKER_28]: Are we pacing it out evenly?

860
02:48:30,533 --> 02:48:35,498
[SPEAKER_28]: I would love to understand more about that for these items.

861
02:48:35,658 --> 02:48:45,547
[SPEAKER_28]: The eHealth software, the transitioning the servers, the instructional materials, robotics and ELA, the open architecture and technology upgrades.

862
02:48:48,198 --> 02:48:49,619
[SPEAKER_23]: I got it, yeah.

863
02:48:50,079 --> 02:48:57,262
[SPEAKER_12]: So regarding what you were talking about curriculum, for most of those, those would be a yearly cost.

864
02:48:57,682 --> 02:49:04,044
[SPEAKER_12]: Robotics specifically, we know it would be a yearly cost, a program that complex that we want to continue it.

865
02:49:04,324 --> 02:49:09,626
[SPEAKER_12]: It wouldn't be something like a Holt-Mifflin where we pay three years for it and we get to keep it.

866
02:49:09,946 --> 02:49:11,227
[SPEAKER_12]: That would be a yearly cost.

867
02:49:12,007 --> 02:49:16,669
[SPEAKER_12]: Another thing you had mentioned was the ELA program for the middle school.

868
02:49:17,549 --> 02:49:20,151
[SPEAKER_12]: I believe that's still being reviewed on right now, but again.

869
02:49:20,171 --> 02:49:21,832
[SPEAKER_28]: Right, I know there wasn't a specific number on that.

870
02:49:21,852 --> 02:49:23,233
[SPEAKER_12]: There wasn't a specific, yeah, curriculum.

871
02:49:23,253 --> 02:49:30,958
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, that would, again, I would defer to Superintendent Dr. Talbot on that a little bit more when it comes to curriculum, but I know that they differ.

872
02:49:31,018 --> 02:49:34,420
[SPEAKER_12]: Some are yearly costs, some are you buy the program for three years and you get to keep it.

873
02:49:35,361 --> 02:49:40,724
[SPEAKER_12]: So in that area, but there are some that are definitely a yearly cost that we're hoping to add to the baseline of the budget.

874
02:49:42,175 --> 02:49:43,697
[SPEAKER_28]: That's important to know.

875
02:49:44,598 --> 02:49:49,965
[SPEAKER_28]: And then my other question is I'm wondering about some of these additional costs.

876
02:49:50,025 --> 02:49:52,588
[SPEAKER_28]: I also wasn't sure about the term unavoidable but.

877
02:49:55,510 --> 02:50:11,874
[SPEAKER_28]: things that are either coming off of revolving accounts or there are some things that I understood to have been included in the infusion of override funds that were then going to progress things like transportation, some of the CBA stipend type adjustments, all of those.

878
02:50:11,974 --> 02:50:22,137
[SPEAKER_28]: And so I'm wondering with the anticipation that there would be a two and a half percent increase every year, why those are,

879
02:50:23,273 --> 02:50:28,959
[SPEAKER_28]: additional that we hadn't planned on before kind of above and beyond 2.5 percent.

880
02:50:30,100 --> 02:50:31,202
[SPEAKER_33]: So we.

881
02:50:32,583 --> 02:50:42,274
[SPEAKER_33]: Well first of all the the first bucket of unavoidable expenses was unavoidable and including unsustainable.

882
02:50:42,474 --> 02:50:45,237
[SPEAKER_33]: So for the for some of them.

883
02:50:46,118 --> 02:50:57,484
[SPEAKER_33]: And I take the full responsibility for some of the confusion, but I just felt it was easier to kind of fold them in to that category.

884
02:50:58,765 --> 02:51:06,029
[SPEAKER_33]: But those are certainly, some of that spending can be pushed off to a future fiscal year.

885
02:51:07,330 --> 02:51:11,792
[SPEAKER_33]: It's not unavoidable in the same way that collective bargaining increases are.

886
02:51:16,544 --> 02:51:30,348
[SPEAKER_33]: There was some spending in FY25 that was associated with the collective bargaining contract that got signed for the teachers.

887
02:51:31,028 --> 02:51:35,049
[SPEAKER_33]: Paraprofessionals came later in FY26.

888
02:51:36,969 --> 02:51:42,871
[SPEAKER_33]: And we utilized money that we have in our base budget for

889
02:51:45,001 --> 02:51:45,981
[SPEAKER_33]: collective bargaining.

890
02:51:46,762 --> 02:51:48,223
[SPEAKER_28]: That's the undistributed funds?

891
02:51:48,823 --> 02:51:49,163
[SPEAKER_28]: Yes.

892
02:51:49,663 --> 02:52:03,091
[SPEAKER_33]: So any contracts that aren't settled yet, we anticipate what we think the eventual result of that bargaining is and that gets distributed.

893
02:52:03,492 --> 02:52:11,136
[SPEAKER_33]: And we utilized over a million dollars in stabilization fund to help support that as well.

894
02:52:12,660 --> 02:52:18,422
[SPEAKER_33]: So those funds got spent, and they've become part of the base budget now.

895
02:52:19,502 --> 02:52:28,365
[SPEAKER_33]: So going forward in 27, we're seeing increases over and above the current fiscal year.

896
02:52:29,085 --> 02:52:33,106
[SPEAKER_33]: And we did have the plan in utilizing stabilization funds.

897
02:52:33,146 --> 02:52:37,827
[SPEAKER_33]: We were able to create a fund of a little over $2 million.

898
02:52:40,416 --> 02:52:46,282
[SPEAKER_33]: for the three years that the teacher's contract would be in effect.

899
02:52:46,943 --> 02:52:57,553
[SPEAKER_33]: And then we are slowly reducing that so we don't, we have, because that, they are part of our base budget.

900
02:52:58,594 --> 02:52:59,315
[SPEAKER_33]: We have to

901
02:53:01,645 --> 02:53:02,865
[SPEAKER_33]: replace those funds.

902
02:53:04,106 --> 02:53:10,867
[SPEAKER_33]: And if we used all $2 million in FY26, we'd be faced with replacing $2 million this year.

903
02:53:10,907 --> 02:53:14,248
[SPEAKER_33]: So we do have to replace about $335,000.

904
02:53:14,488 --> 02:53:23,650
[SPEAKER_33]: That's shifting from stabilization fund into general fund in FY27.

905
02:53:25,051 --> 02:53:30,432
[SPEAKER_33]: But hopefully that answers your question about why we have increases in 27.

906
02:53:32,359 --> 02:53:42,543
[SPEAKER_28]: So I guess it was a question around the carryover and when you, you mentioned reserve in here and what that, is reserve the same thing as the undistributed or is there a separate reserve fund?

907
02:53:42,583 --> 02:53:44,924
[SPEAKER_33]: Well the stabilization fund is a reserve.

908
02:53:46,345 --> 02:53:57,950
[SPEAKER_33]: It's to, I mean we might, we may call undistributed funds reserves too but the stabilization fund was designed to help fund

909
02:53:59,077 --> 02:54:03,539
[SPEAKER_33]: the teacher's contract through the three years of their contract.

910
02:54:04,720 --> 02:54:05,040
[SPEAKER_28]: Okay.

911
02:54:05,600 --> 02:54:17,665
[SPEAKER_28]: And the other thing that would be helpful to see in addition to whether this is a piece of a whole or going forward.

