917
02:54:56,362 --> 02:54:59,503
[SPEAKER_14]: Member Olopade, then Member Graham, then Member Parks.

918
02:55:00,745 --> 02:55:01,125
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

919
02:55:02,046 --> 02:55:05,128
[SPEAKER_36]: This is actually to go a little bit off of what Member Ryenfield was mentioning.

920
02:55:05,509 --> 02:55:11,133
[SPEAKER_36]: And I know, I recognize that the unanticipated costs are in that, unanticipated or, you know, under, under expected.

921
02:55:12,174 --> 02:55:17,638
[SPEAKER_36]: That being said, I think $1.5 million cost to the FY26 budget is quite large.

922
02:55:17,658 --> 02:55:24,023
[SPEAKER_36]: And I think that going forward, are there things that we can be doing to kind of plan accordingly, you know, based off of what's changed?

923
02:55:24,363 --> 02:55:25,064
[SPEAKER_36]: A lot of these are,

924
02:55:27,426 --> 02:55:33,293
[SPEAKER_36]: district needs, so they're not things that, you know, again, they're just based off of what's growingly needed by our students and, and our faculty.

925
02:55:33,333 --> 02:55:37,838
[SPEAKER_36]: So, it's hard to kind of pre-plan, but is there budget forecast that we can do?

926
02:55:37,858 --> 02:55:41,862
[SPEAKER_36]: Are there things that we might be able to implement going forward to kind of maybe ideally plan for that?

927
02:55:44,425 --> 02:55:46,167
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, that, that's what I

928
02:55:47,145 --> 02:55:51,347
[SPEAKER_33]: Budget meetings are designed to do with principals and directors.

929
02:55:52,668 --> 02:55:58,891
[SPEAKER_33]: So I think what we've listed out are things that we were not able to predict.

930
02:55:59,631 --> 02:56:03,693
[SPEAKER_33]: But to the extent we can, we try to identify those.

931
02:56:03,733 --> 02:56:07,135
[SPEAKER_33]: So that's part of why we do enrollment projections.

932
02:56:07,891 --> 02:56:17,658
[SPEAKER_33]: why we do class size estimates to help us understand do we need to add staff?

933
02:56:18,519 --> 02:56:20,820
[SPEAKER_33]: Can we shift staff from one area to another?

934
02:56:22,321 --> 02:56:30,267
[SPEAKER_33]: But in some of these cases, these were people moving into MedFed with identified needs.

935
02:56:32,935 --> 02:56:38,120
[SPEAKER_33]: and or a mix of students.

936
02:56:38,520 --> 02:56:55,235
[SPEAKER_33]: There was a couple, you know, a student in special needs can require a certain amount of services in grade 2 and that may change dramatically in grade 3, you know, as they grow older.

937
02:56:58,435 --> 02:57:01,918
[SPEAKER_33]: those are the things that kind of pop up once they occur.

938
02:57:02,339 --> 02:57:12,648
[SPEAKER_33]: And then particularly in the area of special needs where there's IEPs, those are contracts between the school department and the parent.

939
02:57:12,908 --> 02:57:20,575
[SPEAKER_33]: And so they have to, we have to make sure that we are providing the services that are necessary on those documents.

940
02:57:21,648 --> 02:57:21,988
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

941
02:57:22,809 --> 02:57:29,152
[SPEAKER_36]: My second question goes to the professional development that was noted I think on slide 13.

942
02:57:30,793 --> 02:57:37,476
[SPEAKER_36]: It's recommending or it's noting that one-third of 1% of the total budget is going to be going towards PD or like that increase.

943
02:57:38,116 --> 02:57:41,158
[SPEAKER_36]: Is that what is the general norm?

944
02:57:41,278 --> 02:57:43,359
[SPEAKER_36]: Is there a best practice that we're following when it comes to that?

945
02:57:43,399 --> 02:57:44,499
[SPEAKER_36]: Do we have the numbers on that?

946
02:57:44,519 --> 02:57:45,260
[SPEAKER_36]: I'm not quite sure.

947
02:57:47,163 --> 02:58:09,177
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, I think every school system is different but what we did say during the presentation is that for foundation budget, the budget that DESE puts together for MedFed and for any other district, they have an allocation for professional development and it's 1.7 percent of the budget.

948
02:58:13,218 --> 02:58:22,082
[SPEAKER_33]: I'm not aware of any district that spends up to that amount of money, but it's certainly, you know, we're not close to that area.

949
02:58:22,122 --> 02:58:28,444
[SPEAKER_33]: And it wasn't too long ago that we didn't have any budget for professional development in the general fund.

950
02:58:29,064 --> 02:58:35,347
[SPEAKER_33]: We more or less relied on some of the title grants to provide, you know, minimum amount.

951
02:58:37,218 --> 02:58:52,402
[SPEAKER_33]: There should be like an ongoing resources to develop professional development plans and those, the needs of our teachers could, can vary from year to year.

952
02:58:53,042 --> 02:59:02,184
[SPEAKER_33]: We identify, you know, in analyzing data, we might identify gaps that we have to close and that might require training as well.

953
02:59:06,843 --> 02:59:21,012
[SPEAKER_33]: I know in the case of the arts that the director wants a, you know, has identified the need for more robust program at the elementary schools.

954
02:59:21,352 --> 02:59:35,421
[SPEAKER_33]: So that kind of takes development, you know, acquisition of curriculum and then we have to train our teachers to be able to implement it with fidelity.

955
02:59:36,432 --> 02:59:36,732
[SPEAKER_36]: Absolutely.

956
02:59:36,832 --> 02:59:37,173
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

957
02:59:37,353 --> 02:59:39,154
[SPEAKER_36]: And then my final question for the moment.

958
02:59:40,395 --> 02:59:56,149
[SPEAKER_36]: On slide 19, when we talk about the technology infrastructure, that cybersecurity upgrade package, is that recognized because of an emergent issue that came, that the district came aware of, or is that just an ongoing IT, you know, increase or upgrade that we've been working towards?

959
02:59:57,427 --> 02:59:58,188
[SPEAKER_38]: Can you talk to it?

960
02:59:58,728 --> 03:00:10,458
[SPEAKER_38]: So that was an assessment that I did when I got here compared to what I'm used to and what I feel is really needed is to have increased cybersecurity protection so that this is what's called a managed detection response system.

961
03:00:11,098 --> 03:00:20,886
[SPEAKER_38]: So as opposed to a system that just passively sits in the background and we have to monitor and check, this is a company that watches these systems and they take action immediately upon sensing a cybersecurity threat.

962
03:00:21,626 --> 03:00:22,507
[SPEAKER_38]: That's what that system is.

963
03:00:23,027 --> 03:00:23,488
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you so much.

964
03:00:28,107 --> 03:00:30,696
[SPEAKER_15]: Member Graham and then Member Parks, I think it was, and then Member Russo.

965
03:00:32,502 --> 03:00:32,882
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

966
03:00:32,902 --> 03:00:35,803
[SPEAKER_07]: I just wanted to say thank you.

967
03:00:36,003 --> 03:00:38,323
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you to this team for doing this work.

968
03:00:39,623 --> 03:00:44,744
[SPEAKER_07]: When we started working with this revised budget process maybe three years ago now.

969
03:00:46,645 --> 03:00:58,247
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it has allowed us to really have a different kind of conversation both with the community and with our partners at the city council and the mayor's office and

970
03:00:59,827 --> 03:01:04,189
[SPEAKER_07]: It's the kind of transparency I think we all talk about and want and desire.

971
03:01:04,209 --> 03:01:11,013
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think one of the things that Medford is seeing and feeling right now is that transparency comes with discomfort.

972
03:01:13,014 --> 03:01:22,679
[SPEAKER_07]: It's easier to just be mad about somebody doing something behind closed doors than to have to sit in the discomfort of, we don't have that answer just yet, right?

973
03:01:23,280 --> 03:01:26,201
[SPEAKER_07]: That's uncomfortable for people, and I totally get that.

974
03:01:26,301 --> 03:01:29,383
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it allows people to engage with

975
03:01:29,897 --> 03:01:33,619
[SPEAKER_07]: the process in a in a completely different way and I think we're all better for that.

976
03:01:35,039 --> 03:01:42,983
[SPEAKER_07]: And I recognize that that is a lot of work for you all because essentially you're you're preparing like multiple iterations of a budget.

977
03:01:44,103 --> 03:01:49,946
[SPEAKER_07]: So I just wanted to say thank you because I think transparency really matters to people in Medford.

978
03:01:51,166 --> 03:01:53,848
[SPEAKER_07]: And it's a work in progress in terms of how we get there.

979
03:01:53,928 --> 03:01:56,589
[SPEAKER_07]: But like it starts with all of you telling us

980
03:01:57,349 --> 03:02:03,598
[SPEAKER_07]: plainly like what is going to help us meet our instructional vision and what are the obligations that we have to students.

981
03:02:04,599 --> 03:02:06,242
[SPEAKER_07]: So I just wanted to say thank you for all of that.

982
03:02:06,282 --> 03:02:08,185
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it's really really really important.

983
03:02:08,525 --> 03:02:11,930
[SPEAKER_07]: And you know I just like.

984
03:02:12,273 --> 03:02:15,274
[SPEAKER_07]: mark in my calendar that April through June is going to be uncomfortable.

985
03:02:17,334 --> 03:02:18,234
[SPEAKER_07]: Because it is.

986
03:02:18,614 --> 03:02:20,814
[SPEAKER_07]: And it is every year, like good times, bad times.

987
03:02:20,874 --> 03:02:25,115
[SPEAKER_07]: It doesn't matter, because the truth is our students always deserve more than we can give them.

988
03:02:25,175 --> 03:02:28,836
[SPEAKER_07]: That's just sort of how this works.

989
03:02:29,996 --> 03:02:30,776
[SPEAKER_07]: I wish it weren't.

990
03:02:32,416 --> 03:02:41,518
[SPEAKER_07]: And I look forward to all the ways that government can work together federally, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera, federally, federally.

991
03:02:42,200 --> 03:02:47,743
[SPEAKER_07]: And increase funding for things that matter like educating our future.

992
03:02:47,943 --> 03:02:50,985
[SPEAKER_07]: So I just wanted to say thank you for the work.

993
03:02:51,545 --> 03:02:51,965
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you.

994
03:02:52,246 --> 03:03:02,331
[SPEAKER_33]: I you know I just want to say that the you know we every every budget has a story to it.

995
03:03:02,491 --> 03:03:10,856
[SPEAKER_33]: And the story of this one was the unusually high number of unavoidable costs that we got tagged with this year.

996
03:03:11,725 --> 03:03:13,106
[SPEAKER_33]: and looking into next year.

997
03:03:15,409 --> 03:03:19,312
[SPEAKER_33]: So hopefully that's not the new normal.

998
03:03:20,173 --> 03:03:36,028
[SPEAKER_33]: But that has the potential of squeezing out all the other good things that directors need, that Ken Lord needs as well.

999
03:03:37,822 --> 03:03:47,572
[SPEAKER_33]: So that's another reason of trying to get everything on the table so we can work collectively to come to a reasonable bottom line.

1000
03:03:50,595 --> 03:03:51,156
[SPEAKER_14]: Member Parks.

1001
03:03:52,958 --> 03:03:53,338
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1002
03:03:54,479 --> 03:03:58,163
[SPEAKER_08]: Just for clarification, the page 5, the

1003
03:04:01,568 --> 03:04:09,971
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, or six, but really I was just more looking at the addition of eight paraprofessionals, the special education, transportation, but it could apply to any of these.

1004
03:04:10,472 --> 03:04:22,556
[SPEAKER_08]: These are actual costs that were unanticipated this past year that arose that are going to be carried forward in next year's budget.

1005
03:04:23,697 --> 03:04:30,319
[SPEAKER_08]: But we're not accounting for potential new costs that could arise or doing some percentage allocation.

1006
03:04:31,163 --> 03:04:34,304
[SPEAKER_08]: into the requested budget, is that correct?

1007
03:04:35,204 --> 03:04:36,925
[SPEAKER_08]: And I'll finish my question after that.

1008
03:04:36,985 --> 03:04:37,485
[SPEAKER_08]: That is correct.

1009
03:04:37,505 --> 03:05:00,633
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, there could be one thing now that we have our new transportation coordinator on board, what we want to do is go through an exercise of placing all our students into, onto transportation and to see so frequently what happens when you get new students in,

1010
03:05:02,228 --> 03:05:08,132
[SPEAKER_33]: it can be difficult to get them assigned transportation with the current provider that we have.

1011
03:05:09,273 --> 03:05:14,896
[SPEAKER_33]: Just because they're all booked up or they don't want to hire additional drivers depending on what time of the year it is.

1012
03:05:16,117 --> 03:05:22,701
[SPEAKER_33]: So it forces us to go out and look for independent contractors to fill that need.

1013
03:05:22,881 --> 03:05:29,125
[SPEAKER_33]: Now, there could be opportunities to get those students into transportation we're already buying.

1014
03:05:31,039 --> 03:05:47,433
[SPEAKER_33]: What mainly we tried for new costs that we haven't taken into account, we always try to keep a balance of circuit breaker funds on tap that's unallocated.

1015
03:05:49,390 --> 03:06:01,839
[SPEAKER_33]: We want to use it for a future year, but if we have to use it in the current year to meet new students, then that's our kind of safety net for that.

1016
03:06:02,619 --> 03:06:02,880
[SPEAKER_14]: Okay.

1017
03:06:05,902 --> 03:06:06,222
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

1018
03:06:06,522 --> 03:06:06,802
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

1019
03:06:06,922 --> 03:06:07,563
[SPEAKER_14]: Member Russo?

1020
03:06:08,724 --> 03:06:09,164
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you.

1021
03:06:10,045 --> 03:06:13,807
[SPEAKER_31]: You know, the professional development line item is fascinating in 2001.

1022
03:06:15,473 --> 03:06:26,961
[SPEAKER_31]: The state budget actually had a mandatory spending, which would have put us, adjusted for inflation, at spending almost a million dollars this year on professional development.

1023
03:06:27,481 --> 03:06:30,503
[SPEAKER_31]: The 1.7 would put us at 1.46 million.

1024
03:06:30,663 --> 03:06:32,204
[SPEAKER_31]: That's for last year's budget, by the way.

1025
03:06:33,025 --> 03:06:39,349
[SPEAKER_31]: A lot of the stuff that we want to do in the district requires professional development.

1026
03:06:40,210 --> 03:06:42,231
[SPEAKER_31]: A few years ago, I was going on about

1027
03:06:44,090 --> 03:06:49,140
[SPEAKER_31]: restorative justice, which is a massive professional development effort, multi-year professional development effort.

1028
03:06:49,577 --> 03:07:07,548
[SPEAKER_31]: And I know there's some of that going on, but we can't pretend that for a quarter of a million dollars, we're actually training up 800 employees in a way that would meet the goals of these providers of this instructional material.

1029
03:07:08,529 --> 03:07:15,033
[SPEAKER_31]: So I just wanted to point out that, I mean, I don't know what the professional development budgets are everywhere.

1030
03:07:15,493 --> 03:07:15,893
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm sure in 2001,

1031
03:07:17,378 --> 03:07:39,387
[SPEAKER_31]: A lot of communities lost their minds when they were required to spend that much money because if after 25 years we're still only coming to a quarter of what they thought was a good idea in 2001, that tells me that we are, it's sort of like our maintenance staff, it's like way out on the,

1032
03:07:40,096 --> 03:07:42,717
[SPEAKER_31]: end of a bell curve of what's appropriate spending.

1033
03:07:44,958 --> 03:07:47,159
[SPEAKER_31]: The other, I just wanted to make that point.

1034
03:07:47,860 --> 03:08:01,746
[SPEAKER_31]: The other thing though about how we deal with these unanticipated expenses, like the way a district that is well funded and does that is they actually budget more than they need and they put that into a stabilization fund and it sits there.

1035
03:08:02,046 --> 03:08:08,189
[SPEAKER_31]: And then just like with, you know, like we don't have a snowstorm for a decade and then you have snowmageddon.

1036
03:08:09,032 --> 03:08:14,597
[SPEAKER_31]: And if you budget for the amount of snow you typically get, then you're really in trouble when snowmageddon hits.

1037
03:08:15,317 --> 03:08:17,539
[SPEAKER_31]: So we're still in my mind.

1038
03:08:18,692 --> 03:08:29,758
[SPEAKER_31]: far away from being able to set up stabilization funds where we sit on millions of dollars waiting for the day when there's unanticipated expenses.

1039
03:08:31,779 --> 03:08:40,483
[SPEAKER_31]: I hope we can get there because as everyone in this room knows, when you have a surprise 20 students that need a lot of stuff,

1040
03:08:43,061 --> 03:08:46,384
[SPEAKER_31]: We will provide that even if the consequence is laying off staff.

1041
03:08:46,524 --> 03:08:50,108
[SPEAKER_31]: Like, we don't have a choice but to provide that, and we shouldn't have a choice.

1042
03:08:50,688 --> 03:09:05,261
[SPEAKER_31]: But without that stabilization option, we would perhaps come to city council, or we would have a mid-year deficit and have to close it, which is a horrible idea, to have to go through that.

1043
03:09:07,883 --> 03:09:10,285
[SPEAKER_31]: I do hope that this is not the new normal.

1044
03:09:10,485 --> 03:09:11,385
[SPEAKER_31]: I feel like we won't know.

1045
03:09:12,746 --> 03:09:24,234
[SPEAKER_31]: My question though, I did have a question somewhere in all that, was are any of these things, these unanticipated expenses, well, let me rephrase that.

1046
03:09:25,414 --> 03:09:32,179
[SPEAKER_31]: Does the size of these unanticipated expenses, any of that related to tariffs or inflation?

1047
03:09:35,341 --> 03:09:36,962
[SPEAKER_31]: That you know, I mean.

1048
03:09:37,705 --> 03:09:38,365
[SPEAKER_31]: No, okay.

1049
03:09:38,986 --> 03:09:40,166
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, good.

1050
03:09:40,886 --> 03:09:49,790
[SPEAKER_33]: I should say too that the spending is occurring all throughout the year.

1051
03:09:49,870 --> 03:09:57,653
[SPEAKER_33]: So what we presented tonight is the fully annualized cost of that spending.

1052
03:09:58,074 --> 03:10:03,436
[SPEAKER_33]: And that is not the hit on this year's budget.

1053
03:10:04,810 --> 03:10:09,933
[SPEAKER_33]: Although we're having to address that, you know, in our budget projections.

1054
03:10:10,253 --> 03:10:18,537
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah, I mean, the way I feel like we typically are also solving this is we're not hiring critical positions we need because we won't have the money if we do.

1055
03:10:19,277 --> 03:10:24,340
[SPEAKER_31]: And, you know, we have school district, school committee and we have superintendent goals.

1056
03:10:24,980 --> 03:10:28,362
[SPEAKER_31]: And a lot of that hiring is a big part of meeting those goals.

1057
03:10:28,682 --> 03:10:31,283
[SPEAKER_31]: So not hiring people because we're gonna run out of money.

1058
03:10:31,874 --> 03:10:37,877
[SPEAKER_31]: because of unanticipated costs is really pushing us, you know, is not meeting our goals.

1059
03:10:38,498 --> 03:10:49,584
[SPEAKER_31]: And it's really hard to you know, when we look at the actual budget book, we'll see a number of positions that say, you know, unfilled or whatever the, the language is.

1060
03:10:50,925 --> 03:10:55,988
[SPEAKER_31]: And I think that like, we don't really have time to get into that level of detail in these meetings.

1061
03:10:56,068 --> 03:11:00,170
[SPEAKER_31]: But like, the consequence of not having those people is real.

1062
03:11:00,646 --> 03:11:02,587
[SPEAKER_31]: If it wasn't, we wouldn't even budget for them, right?

1063
03:11:02,667 --> 03:11:05,169
[SPEAKER_31]: Like, we're not hiring extra staff to stand around.

1064
03:11:06,510 --> 03:11:09,792
[SPEAKER_31]: So, I don't know where I was going with that exactly.

1065
03:11:09,852 --> 03:11:10,792
[SPEAKER_31]: It's getting late and I'm hungry.

1066
03:11:10,812 --> 03:11:12,133
[SPEAKER_31]: So, thank you.

1067
03:11:12,153 --> 03:11:20,318
[SPEAKER_15]: Okay, are we ready to go on to number four, gone green billing, fiscal year 25?

1068
03:11:20,358 --> 03:11:27,323
[SPEAKER_15]: Kenneth Lord, Chief Operating Officer, and Noah Velez, Director of Finance.

1069
03:11:31,946 --> 03:11:32,968
[SPEAKER_12]: Hey everyone, it's me again.

1070
03:11:35,012 --> 03:11:35,533
[SPEAKER_12]: Welcome back.

1071
03:11:37,356 --> 03:11:38,257
[SPEAKER_12]: Here with my best friend, Ken.

1072
03:11:41,727 --> 03:11:49,093
[SPEAKER_38]: A few weeks ago, we received a series of invoices from Gone Green, which is our electrical subcontractor who comes in and does a lot of the work.

1073
03:11:49,574 --> 03:11:50,995
[SPEAKER_38]: These are from fiscal 25.

1074
03:11:51,175 --> 03:11:56,880
[SPEAKER_38]: They're a series of invoices that were not processed on our end for payment, but they were received.

1075
03:11:57,500 --> 03:12:01,704
[SPEAKER_38]: And so we're here seeking permission to submit those to payment for this fiscal year.

1076
03:12:02,164 --> 03:12:09,210
[SPEAKER_38]: So we do need your approval and city council's approval in order to pay something out of this fiscal year that occurred in the last fiscal year.

1077
03:12:11,312 --> 03:12:15,856
[SPEAKER_38]: These invoices, it's not entirely clear to us where the failure was.

1078
03:12:15,936 --> 03:12:17,017
[SPEAKER_38]: We know what happened.

1079
03:12:17,037 --> 03:12:20,319
[SPEAKER_38]: The invoice was received and we're not processed for payment.

1080
03:12:21,140 --> 03:12:26,184
[SPEAKER_38]: We've put new systems in place and there were some systems already put in place to try to prevent this in the future.

1081
