1157
03:16:03,044 --> 03:16:07,609
[SPEAKER_15]: Presentations of Student Advisory Council Student Survey on Lunch and Transportation.

1158
03:16:07,810 --> 03:16:08,090
[SPEAKER_15]: Welcome.

1159
03:16:19,783 --> 03:16:28,706
[SPEAKER_06]: Hello everyone we'll try to be a bit quick because we know how late it is but it's also an important thing to talk about so I don't think that we want to rush too much.

1160
03:16:29,306 --> 03:16:44,251
[SPEAKER_06]: We sent a survey a couple weeks ago just sort of trying to gauge the positive student opinion on the state of buses on the state of school lunch in light of the schedule changes for this year as well as the implementation of bus barriers.

1161
03:16:46,612 --> 03:16:48,413
[SPEAKER_06]: continued implementation of bus barriers.

1162
03:16:48,433 --> 03:17:02,762
[SPEAKER_06]: We just wanted to see how these changes sort of affected schools, students in the district as well as sort of evaluate what changes needed to be made, could be made or what concerns may or may not already be being addressed in the district.

1163
03:17:05,213 --> 03:17:07,914
[SPEAKER_06]: So starting with maybe lunch, our lunch survey.

1164
03:17:08,014 --> 03:17:09,235
[SPEAKER_06]: These were two separate surveys.

1165
03:17:10,315 --> 03:17:11,816
[SPEAKER_06]: We should have the response numbers on these.

1166
03:17:13,156 --> 03:17:18,819
[SPEAKER_06]: So we just started, we wanted to sort of see what, how, how much kids were getting school lunch.

1167
03:17:19,379 --> 03:17:23,061
[SPEAKER_06]: And a pretty sizable portion of students get school lunch every day.

1168
03:17:23,161 --> 03:17:26,522
[SPEAKER_06]: So that means that anything that affects the quality of.

1169
03:17:29,645 --> 03:17:32,588
[SPEAKER_06]: going to be affecting a really large portion of Medford High School students.

1170
03:17:33,148 --> 03:17:35,170
[SPEAKER_06]: If you go to the next slide, it's a bit more clear.

1171
03:17:35,190 --> 03:17:43,739
[SPEAKER_06]: We sort of broke it down into ranges just to be a bit more readable rather than each number 1 through 10 being in a separate category.

1172
03:17:43,779 --> 03:17:45,761
[SPEAKER_06]: But this is the same data as the graph before.

1173
03:17:51,850 --> 03:17:56,173
[SPEAKER_34]: Yeah, so on this slide, we asked students, to what extent do you feel lunch lines are overcrowded?

1174
03:17:56,773 --> 03:18:04,178
[SPEAKER_34]: And it's interesting, we have a key that says not crowded, and 0% of students said the lunch lines were not crowded at all.

1175
03:18:04,198 --> 03:18:12,224
[SPEAKER_34]: 50% said they were very crowded, 29.7% said crowded, so crowding is a big issue in the lunch lines.

1176
03:18:12,804 --> 03:18:14,065
[SPEAKER_34]: And even just a few days ago,

1177
03:18:14,893 --> 03:18:21,061
[SPEAKER_34]: I forget what the lunch was exactly, but there was a lot of hype around it, causing a lot of pushing and shoving and crowding.

1178
03:18:21,642 --> 03:18:24,165
[SPEAKER_34]: And so that's definitely something we want to address in the future.

1179
03:18:28,150 --> 03:18:31,474
[SPEAKER_06]: This is obviously a very triangular distribution here.

1180
03:18:31,554 --> 03:18:32,535
[SPEAKER_06]: It might be more normal.

1181
03:18:34,674 --> 03:18:37,155
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, there's not a ton that we gleaned here.

1182
03:18:37,215 --> 03:18:39,775
[SPEAKER_06]: We just wanted to see if there was any real trend that we saw.

1183
03:18:40,555 --> 03:18:43,996
[SPEAKER_06]: We see that most of the crowding is moderate.

1184
03:18:44,276 --> 03:18:48,977
[SPEAKER_06]: So we're not seeing students that are extremely distraught.

1185
03:18:49,077 --> 03:18:50,557
[SPEAKER_06]: Most students are fine.

1186
03:18:50,577 --> 03:19:01,840
[SPEAKER_06]: Although, of course, if kids are getting punched or kids are having extremely negative physical experiences, at least it's good to know that that is maybe the minority in our sample here.

1187
03:19:05,940 --> 03:19:08,342
[SPEAKER_06]: I guess this is along the same lines, so I'll go again.

1188
03:19:08,362 --> 03:19:13,847
[SPEAKER_06]: So yeah, we see, again, the majority of students are subject to sort of the effects of crowding.

1189
03:19:13,887 --> 03:19:19,833
[SPEAKER_06]: They're subject to this unwanted physical contact or like shoving or whatnot in the last two weeks.

1190
03:19:20,173 --> 03:19:29,661
[SPEAKER_06]: This is, again, not as concerning as maybe some of our other data points, but we're still seeing, you know, 67% of students being subject to that, which is obviously not what we want to be able to see.

1191
03:19:29,741 --> 03:19:32,484
[SPEAKER_06]: And that means that, you know, this is a thing that needs to be addressed.

1192
03:19:36,650 --> 03:19:43,173
[SPEAKER_34]: And now for this question, we asked students how often they've been unable to eat lunch due to time constraints.

1193
03:19:43,193 --> 03:19:55,478
[SPEAKER_34]: And you see that while that between about 75% of students on either 1 to 10 days have had been unable to eat the lunch they wanted to eat because of time constraints.

1194
03:19:56,198 --> 03:19:57,678
[SPEAKER_34]: And 25% of students said they were fine.

1195
03:19:57,698 --> 03:20:06,242
[SPEAKER_34]: If you just sum up all of those points from 1 to 10, you see 75% of students were unable to eat all the food they wanted due to time constraints.

1196
03:20:06,744 --> 03:20:19,188
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, and, and really this is a, a really important slide to look at here because we see that 25, almost 26% of students every day in the last two weeks were, were unable to eat all the food that they wanted.

1197
03:20:19,228 --> 03:20:25,010
[SPEAKER_06]: Not because of the, the school lunch didn't provide the food for them, but because students have very limited time.

1198
03:20:25,670 --> 03:20:27,730
[SPEAKER_06]: And we saw that with the decrease in time in the schedule.

1199
03:20:27,770 --> 03:20:32,812
[SPEAKER_06]: We've also seen, especially I've looked at a couple of student complaints and talked to other members of student representatives.

1200
03:20:33,332 --> 03:20:35,513
[SPEAKER_06]: One of the concerns that we've seen is that

1201
03:20:36,249 --> 03:20:48,054
[SPEAKER_06]: Because lunch times are shorter, students have to go into the line earlier into the lunch to get their food to have time to eat, which means that the lunch line is longer at a time, which means kids have to get there earlier, which means the lunch line is longer.

1202
03:20:48,094 --> 03:20:51,215
[SPEAKER_06]: And so we see this sort of confounding effect that makes it more difficult.

1203
03:20:51,736 --> 03:20:56,998
[SPEAKER_06]: And that was some of the things that we heard in maybe the open response sections of this that inform this question.

1204
03:21:03,183 --> 03:21:08,105
[SPEAKER_34]: Yeah, then we asked students, would they think railings or belt barriers would improve the state of the lunch lines?

1205
03:21:08,125 --> 03:21:23,971
[SPEAKER_34]: Because currently it's kind of just this bottleneck that happens where you have, like, at minimum three different lines kind of going into the narrow doorway, with people coming in from all angles trying to get lunch in time so they can't have time to eat all their lunch.

1206
03:21:24,551 --> 03:21:28,513
[SPEAKER_34]: We see about 73% of students said no, they don't think it would improve the state.

1207
03:21:28,613 --> 03:21:31,434
[SPEAKER_34]: And then 26% of students said they would improve the state.

1208
03:21:32,958 --> 03:21:37,321
[SPEAKER_06]: So again, this doesn't seem like the best solution, at least by popular opinion.

1209
03:21:37,341 --> 03:21:42,604
[SPEAKER_06]: So we would be looking at maybe other possible answers to this issue.

1210
03:21:42,644 --> 03:21:44,526
[SPEAKER_06]: And we heard a couple of them in open response.

1211
03:21:48,188 --> 03:21:50,930
[SPEAKER_06]: I think what are some final main takeaways we took for student loans?

1212
03:21:51,010 --> 03:21:54,852
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course, there was complaints of food and all of that sort of stuff.

1213
03:21:54,892 --> 03:22:02,017
[SPEAKER_06]: But we also understand that that is not really the things that we'd be looking at to solve in the short term, things that are, you know,

1214
03:22:02,784 --> 03:22:04,104
[SPEAKER_06]: We want to look at things that are obtainable.

1215
03:22:04,144 --> 03:22:06,265
[SPEAKER_06]: We want to identify where the real problems areas are.

1216
03:22:06,725 --> 03:22:11,686
[SPEAKER_06]: We want to try to enable a better lunch experience for students of Medford High.

1217
03:22:12,146 --> 03:22:21,948
[SPEAKER_06]: And so looking at our data, looking at all the open response questions, I think I'd really, again, like to accentuate the fact that because of purely time constraints, students aren't able to eat the food that is provided to them.

1218
03:22:22,288 --> 03:22:28,529
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not that we're not providing students with enough food necessarily, but that they just simply cannot consume it in the time that's provided.

1219
03:22:28,709 --> 03:22:33,072
[SPEAKER_06]: And maybe that's because they're talking to their friends and they're not doing the things that they should be doing during lunch.

1220
03:22:33,112 --> 03:22:34,593
[SPEAKER_06]: It's possible that there are other issues.

1221
03:22:35,093 --> 03:22:39,075
[SPEAKER_06]: But we believe that that really needs addressing because 26% is just unacceptable in my opinion.

1222
03:22:45,717 --> 03:22:50,141
[SPEAKER_34]: Yeah, and so these next few slides will go into the bus schedule survey we put out.

1223
03:22:50,721 --> 03:22:53,724
[SPEAKER_34]: At first, here are just a few demographics about how students get to school.

1224
03:22:54,084 --> 03:23:00,991
[SPEAKER_34]: With most students taking the bus, either the yellow bus, like the MBTA, in the morning with 60% of students.

1225
03:23:01,771 --> 03:23:07,596
[SPEAKER_34]: And then walking is 10%, car or carpool is like 51%, bike 4.8%, and then some others, just 1%.

1226
03:23:13,977 --> 03:23:16,678
[SPEAKER_34]: You can select multiple ways you get to school.

1227
03:23:16,958 --> 03:23:17,198
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

1228
03:23:19,739 --> 03:23:23,460
[SPEAKER_06]: We saw, again, an increase in bus ridership on the way home.

1229
03:23:23,500 --> 03:23:24,680
[SPEAKER_06]: This, of course, makes sense.

1230
03:23:25,581 --> 03:23:29,642
[SPEAKER_06]: Parents are not available to get their kids to school in the evening a lot of the time.

1231
03:23:30,622 --> 03:23:36,524
[SPEAKER_06]: So that just should be probably an area of greater focus, looking into those results in the evening than it is in the morning.

1232
03:23:39,643 --> 03:23:42,604
[SPEAKER_06]: We again wanted to just get a pulse on general bus ridership.

1233
03:23:43,345 --> 03:23:52,789
[SPEAKER_06]: And again, four to five days, you know, 68, 70% of students, roughly 70% is again a decent portion of the student base at Medford High School.

1234
03:23:52,889 --> 03:23:56,691
[SPEAKER_06]: So this, you know, fixes changes to this would be changes to,

1235
03:23:58,904 --> 03:24:02,626
[SPEAKER_06]: to the lives, improvement of the lives of most students at Medford High School.

1236
03:24:02,646 --> 03:24:10,130
[SPEAKER_06]: And we can see that, you know, almost 90% of students take buses, utilize the buses that are provided, which is, again, a significant portion, even if it's not every day.

1237
03:24:13,712 --> 03:24:25,399
[SPEAKER_34]: Then this is just looking at the demographics in which buses are the most popular to take, with the 134 being the most of 41.9% of students, and then the yellow bus being the least of 21.5% of students.

1238
03:24:27,417 --> 03:24:34,940
[SPEAKER_34]: And a lot of this goes into our consideration on ways to organize the bus pickup area.

1239
03:24:35,400 --> 03:24:54,228
[SPEAKER_34]: For instance, having maybe designated spots that are closer to the sidewalk or just closer to like the crosswalk that are more, is more open, which would allow like for like the 134 and 101, a greater amount of students who take that, take those buses, they can have more space to line up, whereas maybe the yellow bus or the 95 can,

1240
03:24:55,972 --> 03:24:59,975
[SPEAKER_34]: have spots further along the sidewalk where there's less space but also less students.

1241
03:25:00,055 --> 03:25:03,858
[SPEAKER_34]: And so just trying to find ways to better coordinate the bus.

1242
03:25:04,158 --> 03:25:07,501
[SPEAKER_06]: I want to make two clarifications just for the data on this slide show.

1243
03:25:07,901 --> 03:25:12,705
[SPEAKER_06]: This question, there's less responses because of course the students that do not take buses cannot answer this question.

1244
03:25:12,745 --> 03:25:14,046
[SPEAKER_06]: In fact, they weren't served this question.

1245
03:25:14,666 --> 03:25:23,353
[SPEAKER_06]: But then also, there are the students that are taking buses only one or two days a week or less than one day a week to go to the library or whatnot.

1246
03:25:24,533 --> 03:25:29,635
[SPEAKER_06]: may mess up these results because these aren't weighted by how many days students take buses.

1247
03:25:30,876 --> 03:25:40,640
[SPEAKER_06]: So this might be some of the reason why the 134 is higher just because it goes by Manfred Square and the library, but we still think that it's generally representative based off of other data.

1248
03:25:41,760 --> 03:25:49,123
[SPEAKER_06]: Also just for representatives that haven't surveyed the way that the bus system works just in front of our school, haven't been there because I think that I'm not sure.

1249
03:25:50,385 --> 03:25:51,207
[SPEAKER_06]: just who is aware.

1250
03:25:51,227 --> 03:25:57,721
[SPEAKER_06]: There's a bus lane on the, if you're coming up the hill on the left side of the school, where all the buses will go through.

1251
03:25:58,593 --> 03:26:06,936
[SPEAKER_06]: And there are currently in place aluminum barriers that we put up this year to sort of prevent students from falling into the buses or into the road.

1252
03:26:07,736 --> 03:26:14,199
[SPEAKER_06]: But we see that they also cause, you know, that might be safer inherently because they're not falling into the dangerous moving vehicles.

1253
03:26:14,239 --> 03:26:17,400
[SPEAKER_06]: But there's also a crowding issue which is introduced which we'll get to later.

1254
03:26:18,320 --> 03:26:20,481
[SPEAKER_06]: And so currently these buses don't have designated spots.

1255
03:26:20,501 --> 03:26:22,062
[SPEAKER_06]: They just sort of go through and park.

1256
03:26:22,142 --> 03:26:24,903
[SPEAKER_06]: And so all the students need to run to their bus when it shows up.

1257
03:26:26,324 --> 03:26:27,385
[SPEAKER_06]: which causes some issues.

1258
03:26:27,445 --> 03:26:31,128
[SPEAKER_06]: So we just want to make sure that we're on the same page of what the current situation is like.

1259
03:26:31,169 --> 03:26:37,835
[SPEAKER_06]: So when we talk about addressing these issues, we have sort of a united thinking.

1260
03:26:42,180 --> 03:26:43,701
[SPEAKER_06]: This question was added late.

1261
03:26:44,402 --> 03:26:46,784
[SPEAKER_06]: So we do not believe that this data is necessarily representative.

1262
03:26:46,844 --> 03:26:48,346
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, 26 is just not enough.

1263
03:26:50,350 --> 03:26:51,191
[SPEAKER_06]: It's just not enough.

1264
03:26:51,992 --> 03:26:57,920
[SPEAKER_06]: But we still see that 76, 77 percent of students that at least responded to this question wanted to, would utilize a late bus.

1265
03:26:58,000 --> 03:27:00,122
[SPEAKER_06]: This other was like probably.

1266
03:27:05,215 --> 03:27:16,317
[SPEAKER_06]: The reality of the situation is if there's 70% of students, even if this is a very small sample, statistically it's likely that still a significant amount of students would be willing to use a late bus even if the error bars are larger than we'd want.

1267
03:27:16,377 --> 03:27:18,698
[SPEAKER_06]: So I think it's still a helpful question.

1268
03:27:19,798 --> 03:27:25,939
[SPEAKER_06]: And there's a lot of, we didn't bother including all of the other responses because students could select other.

1269
03:27:27,460 --> 03:27:29,460
[SPEAKER_06]: But a lot of them were just a mix, you can see.

1270
03:27:30,673 --> 03:27:35,935
[SPEAKER_06]: Very few of them were actually alternative locations, so we just didn't necessarily bother.

1271
03:27:37,336 --> 03:27:53,122
[SPEAKER_06]: But we saw, you know, most of the demand for late bus locations, if we are talking about this, because we understand it would be a budgetary ask, because currently, you know, students that can take a car, students that can take a bike, students that are maybe more advantaged in terms

1272
03:27:54,597 --> 03:28:02,946
[SPEAKER_06]: monetary basis for their families, are able to access the extracurricular activities, are able to stay after with their teachers, are able to do all of these things.

1273
03:28:03,427 --> 03:28:12,537
[SPEAKER_06]: We do not have a late bus, and so with some exceptions, students that have to ride the bus, students that live farther away from the school, because our school is in a more affluent part of Medford.

1274
03:28:13,734 --> 03:28:21,521
[SPEAKER_06]: are put at not only a disadvantage from all the other factors in their life, but also a disadvantage academically.

1275
03:28:21,861 --> 03:28:28,526
[SPEAKER_06]: Like, we are able to come after school on Thursdays and, you know, participate in student involvement and be here.

1276
03:28:28,927 --> 03:28:34,291
[SPEAKER_06]: But, like, you take the car, your parents drive you, or you drive you most of the time.

1277
03:28:34,531 --> 03:28:35,952
[SPEAKER_06]: I, you know, it's a 20-minute walk.

1278
03:28:35,992 --> 03:28:37,313
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not short, but I can do it.

1279
03:28:39,652 --> 03:28:48,178
[SPEAKER_06]: And so, like, we see this selection in our school, in our clubs, in our after-school activities, and we really just want to try and maintain an equitable learning environment.

1280
03:28:48,298 --> 03:28:59,985
[SPEAKER_06]: So even if this doesn't get addressed this fiscal year with the budgetary constraints that we just spent, you know, time talking about, we do think that the lack of a late bus is really hurting our disadvantaged population at Medford High School.

1281
03:29:04,188 --> 03:29:07,150
[SPEAKER_34]: Yeah, and so recently around things like

1282
03:29:07,595 --> 03:29:17,821
[SPEAKER_34]: December, January added a second bus railing as a way because before with only one bus railing, then all the buses would then park in front of that one bus railing to cause a lot of congestion.

1283
03:29:17,881 --> 03:29:23,245
[SPEAKER_34]: And so now there's a second bus railing where generally like the 134 and like 95, for instance, can park at the two of them.

1284
03:29:23,725 --> 03:29:28,648
[SPEAKER_34]: And we asked students, had this improved the bus departure time crowding or safety?

1285
03:29:29,209 --> 03:29:34,592
[SPEAKER_34]: And it was a resounding 61% or 62% said that it did not help a lot at all.

1286
03:29:35,217 --> 03:29:43,991
[SPEAKER_34]: because there's still, and part of that reason could be because one, like, the buses still can only park in front of them, at least that's how that's being coordinated currently.

1287
03:29:44,471 --> 03:29:46,394
[SPEAKER_34]: And so there's still a lot of crowding.

1288
03:29:46,414 --> 03:29:48,578
[SPEAKER_34]: That's like one of the big things we saw in the responses, how.

1289
03:29:49,017 --> 03:29:52,080
[SPEAKER_34]: There's a lot of crowding, a lot of bottlenecks that happen at those two railings.

1290
03:29:52,620 --> 03:30:02,449
[SPEAKER_34]: And we also see that even if a student's bus isn't the one that's pulled up, they still want to stand in front of that railing to make sure that they have a spot for when their bus comes.

1291
03:30:02,989 --> 03:30:11,257
[SPEAKER_34]: And so there's a lot of congestion, a lot of human body density that happens at the bus railings currently.

1292
03:30:11,743 --> 03:30:21,309
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, and again, because the buses don't have designated spots, if students want to have first positions on their bus, be able to sit comfortably down, which of course the students want to do on their long bus rides home.

1293
03:30:22,309 --> 03:30:23,770
[SPEAKER_06]: They need to be ready by the bus railings.

1294
03:30:23,990 --> 03:30:25,291
[SPEAKER_06]: They don't know which bus is going to come.

1295
03:30:25,311 --> 03:30:26,932
[SPEAKER_06]: They don't know where the buses are going to park.

1296
03:30:27,132 --> 03:30:35,497
[SPEAKER_06]: And so when, you know, I saw today, literally outside the school when I was leaving, the 134, I believe, no, 101 was very late.

1297
03:30:35,577 --> 03:30:44,482
[SPEAKER_06]: And so you had a bunch of the kids sitting around, and then when the bus pulled up to one of the railings, they had, they like, this sort of cloud of kids ran into the other people that were waiting for the 134.

1298
03:30:46,183 --> 03:30:51,047
[SPEAKER_06]: because they don't have designated spots and so students just have to sort of move as a group to the location.

1299
03:30:51,067 --> 03:31:06,016
[SPEAKER_06]: And so in these sort of other categories we saw either sentiment of like it didn't improve significantly or we saw that like there was still significant crowding because of these issues that I just talked about.

1300
03:31:06,076 --> 03:31:08,358
[SPEAKER_06]: These were the main sort of other responses in this category.

1301
03:31:08,698 --> 03:31:12,801
[SPEAKER_06]: We couldn't include them all but those were generally the sum of what they were talking about.

1302
03:31:16,165 --> 03:31:23,130
[SPEAKER_06]: Here, going along with this idea, we see a significant quantity of students think that individual locations would help.

1303
03:31:23,250 --> 03:31:27,433
[SPEAKER_06]: And this is with still bus railings, which the students were saying were not beneficial before.

1304
03:31:27,473 --> 03:31:35,578
[SPEAKER_06]: So that negative percentage, we believe, is at least significantly attributed to students that were previously saying that they didn't want bus railings.

1305
03:31:35,918 --> 03:31:40,561
[SPEAKER_06]: And almost all of the other category here were people saying, yes, individual locations are good.

1306
03:31:40,861 --> 03:31:42,863
[SPEAKER_06]: We just do not want the bus railings present there.

1307
03:31:44,284 --> 03:31:50,529
[SPEAKER_06]: And so we think that we would like to do another version of the survey, just without the railings, ask about individual locations.

1308
03:31:50,589 --> 03:32:03,521
[SPEAKER_06]: But based off of, you know, anecdotal student opinions, we've talked to a couple other students and just based off the results of this forum, we feel like as, you know, a lower cost option here, of course, require coordination with the MBTA.

1309
03:32:03,921 --> 03:32:05,703
[SPEAKER_06]: But just like in the middle schools,

1310
03:32:06,743 --> 03:32:14,808
[SPEAKER_06]: If we can just designate certain portions of that, of the sidewalk area to the, outside the, what is it called?

1311
03:32:15,448 --> 03:32:16,508
[SPEAKER_06]: Like that courtyard?

1312
03:32:16,608 --> 03:32:17,389
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

1313
03:32:17,409 --> 03:32:17,949
[SPEAKER_06]: The west courtyard?

1314
03:32:17,989 --> 03:32:18,730
[SPEAKER_06]: The west courtyard.

1315
03:32:18,810 --> 03:32:34,738
[SPEAKER_06]: If we can, if we can allocate specific areas for the four different buses outside the west courtyard, I think we and most other students believe that that would significantly help aid in a lot of issues we see with buses as sort of a more easily implemented solution.

1316
03:32:36,842 --> 03:32:37,162
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

1317
03:32:37,582 --> 03:32:45,745
[SPEAKER_15]: I love that you did a survey and are telling us what the students feel is necessary and issues and concerns.

1318
03:32:46,086 --> 03:32:47,826
[SPEAKER_15]: I really appreciate the presentation.

1319
03:32:48,286 --> 03:32:50,207
[SPEAKER_15]: If there's any questions, Member Reinfeldt?

1320
03:32:50,327 --> 03:32:54,889
[SPEAKER_28]: Not questions so much, just to say we just met our new transportation manager.

1321
03:32:54,909 --> 03:32:55,989
[SPEAKER_28]: Obviously, she's new.

1322
03:32:56,069 --> 03:33:02,572
[SPEAKER_28]: I assume you've met with her, but some of this on the bus front certainly seems like it could be very quickly pilotable.

1323
03:33:04,173 --> 03:33:11,058
[SPEAKER_28]: And I would love to see the results, because we've, the late bus, we talked about that on a, I think it was our Zoom only meeting.

1324
03:33:11,558 --> 03:33:17,943
[SPEAKER_28]: So I'm excited to see that analysis once our new transportation manager kind of gets feet under her.

1325
03:33:17,963 --> 03:33:20,404
[SPEAKER_28]: I don't want to throw everything at her the first week.

1326
03:33:20,424 --> 03:33:24,147
[SPEAKER_28]: So I'm excited about that there's really clear actionable things.

1327
03:33:25,028 --> 03:33:29,130
[SPEAKER_28]: My question on the, not a question, I promise, on the,

1328
03:33:31,037 --> 03:33:32,097
[SPEAKER_28]: No, it's a question.

1329
03:33:32,177 --> 03:33:33,017
[SPEAKER_28]: I'm going to ask it.

1330
03:33:35,038 --> 03:33:36,458
[SPEAKER_28]: So there are questions of time.

1331
03:33:36,498 --> 03:33:37,558
[SPEAKER_28]: There's questions of space.

1332
03:33:37,618 --> 03:33:41,859
[SPEAKER_28]: Time turns out to be one of those really complicated things with lots of ripple effect.

1333
03:33:43,099 --> 03:33:44,780
[SPEAKER_28]: But the space question is interesting.

1334
03:33:44,820 --> 03:33:49,240
[SPEAKER_28]: I think we heard some strong feelings about railings, particularly in cafeterias.

1335
03:33:49,280 --> 03:33:52,601
[SPEAKER_28]: I have all kinds of questions about how this applies at the elementary school.

1336
03:33:52,621 --> 03:33:56,982
[SPEAKER_28]: But the question for you is, we are currently thinking about a new high school in Medford.

1337
03:33:58,122 --> 03:33:58,962
[SPEAKER_28]: There's an opportunity.

1338
03:33:59,042 --> 03:34:06,385
[SPEAKER_28]: And so I guess my question is, what advice would you have to the design team, knowing that we are still in that collecting input phase?

1339
03:34:06,745 --> 03:34:09,286
[SPEAKER_28]: Or maybe this is something you could write up and send separately.

1340
03:34:09,366 --> 03:34:13,688
[SPEAKER_28]: But what would the student body of Medford High School want to see in the cafeteria?

1341
03:34:13,768 --> 03:34:16,950
[SPEAKER_28]: Or maybe you've already had that conversation with the architects.

1342
03:34:17,150 --> 03:34:17,550
[SPEAKER_28]: I don't know.

1343
03:34:18,090 --> 03:34:21,671
[SPEAKER_28]: But this seems like a great opportunity to look at the space that's needed.

1344
03:34:21,851 --> 03:34:25,133
[SPEAKER_28]: And are there ways to improve that traffic, that crowding,

1345
03:34:25,813 --> 03:34:28,538
[SPEAKER_28]: physical contact by changing the layout.

1346
03:34:28,558 --> 03:34:35,210
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, I mean we definitely want to do, I think we'd want to do another plebiscite, another survey, because

1347
03:34:37,322 --> 03:34:38,682
[SPEAKER_06]: The cafeteria question is hard.

1348
03:34:39,302 --> 03:34:43,543
[SPEAKER_06]: If it was easy and it wasn't cost prohibitive, then it would not be a problem.

1349
03:34:44,043 --> 03:34:48,064
[SPEAKER_06]: And some of the issue of the cafeteria is the design of the cafeteria space.

1350
03:34:48,084 --> 03:34:49,244
[SPEAKER_06]: That is most certainly true.

1351
03:34:50,024 --> 03:34:56,606
[SPEAKER_06]: Students have to go to the far side, and then when they come out of the cafeteria line, they have to intersect back with the crowd that's already there.

1352
03:34:56,986 --> 03:34:59,826
[SPEAKER_06]: So there isn't capability for smooth flow.

1353
03:35:00,947 --> 03:35:02,747
[SPEAKER_28]: Sounds like the driveways at the high school.

1354
03:35:02,767 --> 03:35:02,847
[SPEAKER_28]: Sure.

1355
03:35:03,428 --> 03:35:05,769
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, that is an apt comparison.

1356
03:35:06,730 --> 03:35:23,799
[SPEAKER_06]: And then I think this is, you know, it's maybe, I think buses are a bit easier to talk about just because the student opinion has been more united in terms of possible solutions.

1357
03:35:23,959 --> 03:35:27,381
[SPEAKER_06]: I think we always have a dissenting opinion whenever we do anything like this.

1358
03:35:27,481 --> 03:35:29,422
[SPEAKER_06]: It's just how it works, but.

1359
03:35:29,582 --> 03:35:31,683
[SPEAKER_28]: We don't know what that's like on school committee at all.

1360
03:35:31,703 --> 03:35:31,803
[SPEAKER_06]: Sure.

1361
03:35:33,063 --> 03:35:35,825
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course, never heard a negative voice ever.

1362
03:35:37,046 --> 03:35:47,475
[SPEAKER_06]: No, but, you know, I think that buses are a bit of an easier problem to address and that also goes into traffic and the traffic flow conversation because if we're expecting you know buses to be lining up.

1363
03:35:49,127 --> 03:35:57,030
[SPEAKER_06]: In parallel, like, at this, like, on the bus lane at the same time, which we do see, but they not, they might need to pass each other, right?

1364
03:35:57,071 --> 03:35:58,431
[SPEAKER_06]: That's a whole nother consideration.

1365
03:35:58,451 --> 03:36:07,835
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, they do that at, you know, the Andrews to some extent, but it's just, I think, I think the current causeway is wide enough.

1366
03:36:09,490 --> 03:36:10,890
[SPEAKER_06]: There are considerations, of course.

1367
03:36:11,011 --> 03:36:23,915
[SPEAKER_06]: I think that it is difficult to give you concrete stuff right now after a preliminary survey, but that is certainly, I think, important feedback that could be provided, and we would love to, I think, provide a write-up or something.

1368
03:36:24,756 --> 03:36:35,706
[SPEAKER_28]: Thank you, and then the other piece I would just urge you to keep in mind with the buses and transportation is thinking about the safety components of people who aren't taking buses and walking, biking, and all of that.

1369
03:36:35,746 --> 03:36:43,514
[SPEAKER_06]: I think the good thing about the way our school is currently set up is that the west courtyard is not the only exit the students can take off the campus.

1370
03:36:43,554 --> 03:36:45,976
[SPEAKER_06]: In fact, I don't even think it's the least, like,

1371
03:36:47,137 --> 03:36:50,581
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not even, in many cases, the closest exit to the bottom of the hill.

1372
03:36:51,021 --> 03:36:57,449
[SPEAKER_06]: So students that are walking, students that are taking their bike often exit out of the front entrance of the school, because then they do not have to deal with the crowd.

1373
03:36:57,729 --> 03:36:59,751
[SPEAKER_06]: Make that more explicit is probably a good idea.

1374
03:37:00,192 --> 03:37:01,974
[SPEAKER_06]: I think that, you know, it is certainly an issue.

1375
03:37:01,994 --> 03:37:03,595
[SPEAKER_06]: There is a choke point, you know, at the...

1376
03:37:05,537 --> 03:37:21,168
[SPEAKER_06]: would be the south corner of the west courtyard, like trying to triangulate, but the corner closer to the main street because that's where the buses pull up, students have to sit there.

1377
03:37:22,569 --> 03:37:31,075
[SPEAKER_06]: So we just want to try and, I think when you talk about bus ridership, and this is the reason why we did this question in the beginning, it's like we want to move the higher volume buses

1378
03:37:32,370 --> 03:37:44,476
[SPEAKER_06]: into the court, is the inner two spots, is the middle two spots next to the courtyard so that those students are in that, you know, location that can hide some more rather than just being on the sidewalk which is, you know, rather skinny and could provide congestion issues.

1379
03:37:45,056 --> 03:37:46,277
[SPEAKER_06]: But yet safety is very important.

1380
03:37:46,577 --> 03:37:59,323
[SPEAKER_06]: That's why the bus railings were there in the first place and so we still have a bit mixed feelings on that because even if they're causing worse crowding, if they stop students from, you know, getting their foot run over by a bus, I know that that was a problem, you know, a couple years back.

1381
03:38:02,877 --> 03:38:04,738
[SPEAKER_06]: Maybe they're still worth it to have in place.

1382
03:38:07,199 --> 03:38:08,860
[SPEAKER_15]: Okay, thank you so much for the presentation.

1383
03:38:09,580 --> 03:38:10,240
[SPEAKER_15]: Dr. Golosi?

1384
03:38:10,580 --> 03:38:11,561
[SPEAKER_13]: I just have one quick question.

1385
03:38:11,721 --> 03:38:14,462
[SPEAKER_13]: You mentioned maybe potentially doing another survey.

1386
03:38:15,122 --> 03:38:21,305
[SPEAKER_13]: On this original survey, do we get a sense of what, did you, was there a question that asked the grade span?

1387
03:38:21,745 --> 03:38:25,247
[SPEAKER_13]: I noticed participation for the lunch varied between 118 to 128 responses.

1388
03:38:25,267 --> 03:38:27,628
[SPEAKER_13]: Do we know what that breakdown was across the 1,200 students?

1389
03:38:33,296 --> 03:38:34,817
[SPEAKER_13]: Like was one particular grade?

1390
03:38:34,877 --> 03:38:37,138
[SPEAKER_06]: Actually, we could pull that information.

1391
03:38:39,399 --> 03:38:42,200
[SPEAKER_06]: I think we didn't explicitly.

1392
03:38:42,560 --> 03:38:44,220
[SPEAKER_06]: We can actually pull some of that information.

1393
03:38:44,321 --> 03:38:47,242
[SPEAKER_06]: We didn't include it on the slideshow because we didn't think it was particularly insightful.

1394
03:38:47,262 --> 03:38:50,163
[SPEAKER_06]: In fact, there were quite a few questions that weren't necessarily included.

1395
03:38:50,283 --> 03:38:57,866
[SPEAKER_06]: But one of the things that we sort of asked was if students felt that the lunch lines were longer or shorter or meaningfully different from previous years.

1396
03:38:58,306 --> 03:39:02,528
[SPEAKER_06]: We saw very mixed results on some of that because a lot of the students

1397
03:39:02,928 --> 03:39:05,129
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course, generally along the consensus.

1398
03:39:06,850 --> 03:39:11,692
[SPEAKER_06]: But we, you know, there was of course an option for students that didn't go to school last year.

1399
03:39:11,712 --> 03:39:13,093
[SPEAKER_06]: So we can certainly pull the ninth graders out.

1400
03:39:13,133 --> 03:39:17,335
[SPEAKER_06]: But yes, that is something we'd like to do sort of going forward is look at those demographics.

1401
03:39:19,276 --> 03:39:21,957
[SPEAKER_06]: But no, unfortunately on this survey we do not have the information.

1402
03:39:21,977 --> 03:39:23,698
[SPEAKER_06]: But that would be a consideration for follow-ups.

1403
03:39:23,798 --> 03:39:25,199
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think that is important.

1404
03:39:25,219 --> 03:39:26,679
[SPEAKER_06]: So thank you for bringing that to our attention.

1405
03:39:27,180 --> 03:39:27,540
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

1406
03:39:30,461 --> 03:39:30,701
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

1407
03:39:36,634 --> 03:39:38,154
[SPEAKER_15]: Do not have any presentations of the public.

1408
03:39:38,174 --> 03:39:39,395
[SPEAKER_15]: We do have continued business.

1409
03:39:39,595 --> 03:39:40,796
[SPEAKER_15]: MSBA project update.

1410
03:39:40,856 --> 03:39:44,537
[SPEAKER_15]: Member Graham, chair of the Medford Comprehensive High School Building Committee.

1411
03:39:44,557 --> 03:39:46,018
[SPEAKER_15]: I'll turn it to you.

1412
03:39:47,185 --> 03:39:47,545
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1413
03:39:47,566 --> 03:39:52,713
[SPEAKER_07]: I will try to be brief and thorough at the same time.

1414
03:39:52,813 --> 03:39:54,114
[SPEAKER_07]: So we'll see how it goes.

1415
03:39:55,036 --> 03:39:55,296
[SPEAKER_07]: OK.

1416
03:39:55,316 --> 03:40:02,085
[SPEAKER_07]: So the first thing I wanted to cover was some conversation around the process where we are the option selection etc.

1417
03:40:02,906 --> 03:40:13,932
[SPEAKER_07]: So as I think you all know, the MSBA asked us to move more quickly from 29 to 3 to 5 options or so than we originally anticipated.

1418
03:40:14,012 --> 03:40:14,932
[SPEAKER_07]: So we have done that.

1419
03:40:15,993 --> 03:40:17,534
[SPEAKER_07]: We have notified the MSBA.

1420
03:40:17,554 --> 03:40:19,955
[SPEAKER_07]: They've acknowledged that they received that.

1421
03:40:20,515 --> 03:40:26,918
[SPEAKER_07]: And they are now working through providing their feedback on our PDP submission.

1422
03:40:27,078 --> 03:40:30,000
[SPEAKER_07]: So all of that is happening and we're expecting

1423
03:40:30,722 --> 03:40:32,864
[SPEAKER_07]: answers from the MSBA in the coming days.

1424
03:40:35,247 --> 03:40:44,698
[SPEAKER_07]: One of the things that I think is noteworthy about the six options is that I don't think there was any clear favorite in all the discussion.

1425
03:40:44,858 --> 03:40:51,185
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think there is a clear winner of any of these options if you are just thinking about the thing that looks

1426
03:40:51,789 --> 03:40:55,190
[SPEAKER_07]: like it's going to work the best for us, because it's a really complicated site.

1427
03:40:55,811 --> 03:41:03,413
[SPEAKER_07]: What the six options do, though, is pretty comprehensively allow us to explore all the facets of what's possible on the site.

1428
03:41:03,914 --> 03:41:05,354
[SPEAKER_07]: So I'm excited about that.

1429
03:41:06,895 --> 03:41:14,938
[SPEAKER_07]: We did hear from the committee lots of questions about things like, could you explore this without needing modulars?

1430
03:41:15,058 --> 03:41:20,460
[SPEAKER_07]: Could you explore this option to look a little bit more like this other option that couldn't go forward, which is all like,

1431
03:41:21,020 --> 03:41:23,462
[SPEAKER_07]: exactly what happens at this phase of design.

1432
03:41:24,383 --> 03:41:41,337
[SPEAKER_07]: Earlier today I did send a form out for the building committee to provide that kind of input to the project team so that the project team can either integrate that into their next iteration of design or provide some documentation about why it can't or it's not possible or it can't.

1433
03:41:42,218 --> 03:41:45,400
[SPEAKER_07]: So all of that is happening right now from a selection perspective.

1434
03:41:46,581 --> 03:41:48,363
[SPEAKER_07]: We don't have plans to

1435
03:41:48,675 --> 03:41:52,138
[SPEAKER_07]: to pair down from six before we get to one.

1436
03:41:52,178 --> 03:41:54,540
[SPEAKER_07]: So we'll go from six to one as our next plan.

1437
03:41:56,261 --> 03:41:59,825
[SPEAKER_07]: Between now and then, a couple of other important things will be happening.

1438
03:42:00,986 --> 03:42:16,579
[SPEAKER_07]: First, we have also today asked for the building committee to provide any suggestions that they have for space changes, whether that is adding or subtracting from the space summary.

1439
03:42:17,562 --> 03:42:30,953
[SPEAKER_07]: And those proposals will be collected up and provided and noticed on the agenda for our meeting on the 27th where we will be considering and voting on anything that might change the space allocation as it was originally envisioned.

1440
03:42:32,494 --> 03:42:36,857
[SPEAKER_07]: Based on whatever is approved in that meeting on the 27th.

1441
03:42:38,111 --> 03:42:51,692
[SPEAKER_07]: A revised request will go to the two estimators on the project for a second round of costing where more things are known about these options and they can get a little bit more.

1442
03:42:53,964 --> 03:43:00,332
[SPEAKER_07]: precise although I say a little bit because I think we're still at the a little bit phase when it comes to cost.

1443
03:43:01,213 --> 03:43:05,659
[SPEAKER_07]: But that next round again is really intended to help us compare the options to each other.

1444
03:43:05,679 --> 03:43:11,987
[SPEAKER_07]: And you know I think we'll see some combination of like changes to space on the 27th.

1445
03:43:14,398 --> 03:43:20,842
[SPEAKER_07]: and yet another combination of options because whatever we eliminate on the 27th is gone forever.

1446
03:43:21,823 --> 03:43:33,031
[SPEAKER_07]: We also have options to carry forward options which you saw some of that in our last costing and we can continue to do that at this phase so that we have sort of all the options on the table.

1447
03:43:34,192 --> 03:43:41,597
[SPEAKER_07]: The group is also slated to come to our meeting here on May 4th with an update and in particular if there are any

1448
03:43:43,138 --> 03:43:50,142
[SPEAKER_07]: edits or comments from the MSBA about the ed plan which again is the purview of this committee.

1449
03:43:51,303 --> 03:43:54,265
[SPEAKER_07]: I would envision that I would envision those being surfaced on the 4th.

1450
03:43:55,365 --> 03:43:59,488
[SPEAKER_07]: We do have a series of upcoming community events scheduled.

1451
03:43:59,888 --> 03:44:01,289
[SPEAKER_07]: The next one is on the 15th.

1452
03:44:02,530 --> 03:44:11,475
[SPEAKER_07]: Last week I also spent some time in the recording studio with our CTE students and Matt and we actually went and did like a

1453
03:44:12,247 --> 03:44:23,116
[SPEAKER_07]: a little like you know virtual walking tour of each of the six options and we sort of talked a little bit about what's to come for each of these options.

1454
03:44:23,156 --> 03:44:24,177
[SPEAKER_07]: So what is the option.

1455
03:44:24,217 --> 03:44:24,537
[SPEAKER_07]: What is it.

1456
03:44:25,337 --> 03:44:26,639
[SPEAKER_07]: What are we seeing in the picture.

1457
03:44:26,699 --> 03:44:27,439
[SPEAKER_07]: What is possible.

1458
03:44:27,479 --> 03:44:28,440
[SPEAKER_07]: What's not possible.

1459
03:44:29,261 --> 03:44:37,107
[SPEAKER_07]: Just to give people an orientation of the six if they haven't tuned in yet so that people can watch those RCT students are

1460
03:44:38,167 --> 03:44:40,909
[SPEAKER_07]: editing and preparing those now.

1461
03:44:40,949 --> 03:44:44,731
[SPEAKER_07]: So you should see those in the coming days which is super exciting.

1462
03:44:46,472 --> 03:45:00,440
[SPEAKER_07]: We also are working on in addition to our community forums a list of events across the spring where we will be out in various places in the community so people can come and ask their live questions.

1463
03:45:01,141 --> 03:45:03,262
[SPEAKER_07]: We are planning a trip to the senior center

1464
03:45:03,807 --> 03:45:07,270
[SPEAKER_07]: the senior center and mailer that will go to every household in Medford.

1465
03:45:08,971 --> 03:45:17,757
[SPEAKER_07]: And then I think the sort of last bucket is maybe like a catch all and just a couple of other things happening last week.

1466
03:45:18,418 --> 03:45:23,141
[SPEAKER_07]: Thanks to suggestion and some guidance from David to disco who is a resident.

1467
03:45:23,862 --> 03:45:28,045
[SPEAKER_07]: We put in a federal grant request for three million dollars to fund

1468
03:45:28,665 --> 03:45:43,011
[SPEAKER_07]: The Medford family network space in the welcome center at least I think substantially based on the current numbers and whether that goes forward this year or perhaps like primes the pump for next year I think either way.

1469
03:45:44,298 --> 03:45:45,378
[SPEAKER_07]: I will take $3 million.

1470
03:45:46,660 --> 03:45:58,550
[SPEAKER_07]: We did meet with Medford REC today and we were talking about the pool and the options for the pool and some of the things from a more visionary perspective that our pool experts here in Medford would like to see us think about and consider.

1471
03:45:58,570 --> 03:46:05,817
[SPEAKER_07]: And Kevin graciously also offered to begin looking for grant funding for the pool.

1472
03:46:06,718 --> 03:46:08,840
[SPEAKER_07]: So we'll take that as well.

1473
03:46:08,900 --> 03:46:10,741
[SPEAKER_07]: So that more to come there.

1474
03:46:11,742 --> 03:46:24,615
[SPEAKER_07]: We did also talk with Kevin from a really preliminary contingency planning space and we start talking about the things that will be impacted on the site during construction.

1475
03:46:25,015 --> 03:46:29,680
[SPEAKER_07]: How do we start to make sure that our full cadre of programming can continue.

1476
03:46:30,278 --> 03:46:31,259
[SPEAKER_07]: through construction.

1477
03:46:31,339 --> 03:46:39,523
[SPEAKER_07]: So if for example we pick a design that builds something on the field that means we'll be displacing soccer and lacrosse and where do they go.

1478
03:46:39,963 --> 03:46:52,230
[SPEAKER_07]: So we're having all those conversations and there's some related work that the city is contemplating around Hormel Stadium so that it can be ready to receive students if it comes to that.

1479
03:46:54,051 --> 03:46:58,233
[SPEAKER_07]: We did also talk with Kevin about

1480
03:46:59,667 --> 03:47:02,369
[SPEAKER_07]: you know other alternatives like the Tufts pool etc.

1481
03:47:02,509 --> 03:47:11,734
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we've had a lot of conversations about the pool and we are exploring every avenue to make the priority of the pool

1482
03:47:13,832 --> 03:47:19,696
[SPEAKER_07]: remain a priority but not drive the entirety of the design decision making about the high school project.

1483
03:47:20,476 --> 03:47:27,220
[SPEAKER_07]: And I don't have any answers for that yet just questions and conversation that we're having particularly with our state delegation.

1484
03:47:28,421 --> 03:47:34,545
[SPEAKER_07]: Our state delegation was in a week and a half ago where we gave them an update on the project and we had lunch at Bistro 489.

1485
03:47:35,765 --> 03:47:42,950
[SPEAKER_07]: And we talked with them about any variety of things on the docket in terms of the project.

1486
03:47:43,690 --> 03:47:51,295
[SPEAKER_07]: We also talked about, you know, my desire to see the state increase reimbursement when you're building vocational programs.

1487
03:47:51,375 --> 03:47:52,756
[SPEAKER_07]: Vocational programs are expensive.

1488
03:47:53,216 --> 03:47:53,917
[SPEAKER_07]: They are the future.

1489
03:47:53,977 --> 03:47:59,080
[SPEAKER_07]: They are the thing that at the state level everyone is talking about, and yet there's like no additional reimbursement.

1490
03:47:59,160 --> 03:48:02,462
[SPEAKER_07]: And in fact, there is a bill, there are multiple bills

1491
03:48:02,912 --> 03:48:11,058
[SPEAKER_07]: that seem to have stripped out the additional reimbursement for vocational programs, which is sad and not aligned with, I think, the future of education.

1492
03:48:11,138 --> 03:48:12,599
[SPEAKER_07]: So hopeful that

1493
03:48:13,631 --> 03:48:15,553
[SPEAKER_07]: we can continue to have that conversation with them.

1494
03:48:16,534 --> 03:48:28,043
[SPEAKER_07]: We are also talking with them because we are in conversation with DCR, who is our biggest, largest neighbor by far, and they all but surround us, actually, on the site when you look at a map.

1495
03:48:28,764 --> 03:48:41,915
[SPEAKER_07]: And we are talking to them about, as well as Friends of the Fells, about both construction, post-construction needs that we have and share with them,

1496
03:48:42,568 --> 03:48:54,197
[SPEAKER_07]: like access to the site in a way that is not just the main sort of access road right now, which would, we think would be mutually beneficial with DCR.

1497
03:48:54,257 --> 03:49:05,785
[SPEAKER_07]: But obviously that brings up lots of planning and permitting sort of questions that create a long tail potentially depending on what, where we go with all of those options in collaboration with DCR.

1498
03:49:06,186 --> 03:49:08,287
[SPEAKER_07]: So we wanted to make sure our state delegation was,

1499
03:49:10,208 --> 03:49:13,130
[SPEAKER_07]: aware of and involved in that discussion early on.

1500
03:49:14,170 --> 03:49:17,512
[SPEAKER_07]: They were extremely supportive and excited about the project.

1501
03:49:18,392 --> 03:49:29,759
[SPEAKER_07]: They raved about the blueberry bread pudding at the bistro and it was a very excellent dessert topping I guess I would say.

1502
03:49:29,779 --> 03:49:36,722
[SPEAKER_07]: And it was it was a good conversation and they're eager to help any way that they can which I think is great.

1503
03:49:38,711 --> 03:49:44,994
[SPEAKER_07]: I think other than that's sort of like a and as fast as possible like roundup of everything that's going on.

1504
03:49:45,034 --> 03:49:48,976
[SPEAKER_07]: But there's like literally tons and tons of planning going on.

1505
03:49:49,016 --> 03:50:00,142
[SPEAKER_07]: I know that the SMMA is talking to the city's traffic engineer about some exciting things that the traffic engineer is suggesting in terms of.

1506
03:50:02,502 --> 03:50:15,447
[SPEAKER_07]: The entrance and exit, this next phase of design will also allow us to look more carefully at circulation around the building, which will improve traffic flow on and off the site.

1507
03:50:15,947 --> 03:50:27,751
[SPEAKER_07]: It will plan for things like where do buses go, where do people go, where do cars go, where do bikes go, et cetera, so much to the point of the conversation that our students were just having with us.

1508
03:50:29,372 --> 03:50:51,472
[SPEAKER_07]: Our site was not planned for any of these things in mind, and I think the most exciting thing that I heard today was that after a pretty thorough walkthrough of our pool space, if the pool remains in its current location, there are some options to still improve that back corner of the building if circulation around the back corner remains an issue.

1509
03:50:51,982 --> 03:50:56,045
[SPEAKER_07]: that I don't think anybody was really thinking about before this detailed walkthrough.

1510
03:50:56,065 --> 03:50:57,025
[SPEAKER_07]: So that was exciting.

1511
03:50:57,045 --> 03:51:00,007
[SPEAKER_07]: And it would not impact the size of the pool, et cetera.

1512
03:51:00,047 --> 03:51:03,069
[SPEAKER_07]: So much more to come on all of this.

1513
03:51:03,710 --> 03:51:05,351
[SPEAKER_07]: But just mark your calendar.

1514
03:51:05,391 --> 03:51:08,813
[SPEAKER_07]: The 415 is our next community forum.

1515
03:51:09,093 --> 03:51:13,436
[SPEAKER_07]: 427 is where we'll take up space change considerations and proposals.

1516
03:51:14,436 --> 03:51:19,980
[SPEAKER_07]: And then the team will be here on May 4 to talk about any feedback on the ed plan.

1517
03:51:21,648 --> 03:51:22,049
[SPEAKER_07]: Questions?

1518
03:51:25,072 --> 03:51:26,994
[SPEAKER_15]: No, thank you for the presentation.

1519
03:51:27,014 --> 03:51:33,322
[SPEAKER_15]: Do you have a question?

1520
03:51:36,479 --> 03:51:40,900
[SPEAKER_15]: We don't have any new businesses or reports requested, but we do have a couple of condolences.

1521
03:51:40,980 --> 03:51:55,725
[SPEAKER_15]: The members of the Medford School Committee expressed its sincerest condolences to the family of David P. Skerry, Medford High School social studies teacher, best buddy's advisor, unified basketball coach, and former varsity basketball coach John Skerry's father.

1522
03:52:00,987 --> 03:52:06,951
[SPEAKER_15]: And the members of the Medford School Committee express their sincere condolences to the family of Lot Max Parisian.

1523
03:52:07,692 --> 03:52:16,678
[SPEAKER_15]: Lot Max graduated from Medford High School in 1978 and served the Medford High School community for many years, most recently as a security monitor from 2019 to 2024.

1524
03:52:16,858 --> 03:52:20,020
[SPEAKER_15]: If we all may rise for a moment of silence, please.

1525
03:52:30,467 --> 03:52:30,747
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

1526
03:52:32,691 --> 03:52:42,383
[SPEAKER_15]: Our next regular meeting will be next Monday, April 13th, 2026, here in the Alden Memorial Chambers and via Zoom.

1527
03:52:43,604 --> 03:52:44,946
[SPEAKER_28]: Motion to adjourn.

1528
03:52:45,066 --> 03:52:50,011
[SPEAKER_15]: Motion to adjourn by Member Reinfeldt, seconded by Member Mastroboni.

